
øNotes                  Development Notes

 06/26/89

        Added ARRAY to the list of available data structures.

        You don't need to put a BYE at the end of you program any more,
        as it is built into the initialization code.

        Corrected compiler so it only includes variables and arrays when
        they are referenced by an application or application referenced
        word.  This reduced the data segment overhead from about 150
        bytes to two bytes if no data is referenced.

        Added two target compiler optimizers, the first looks for an
        "LODSW" (POP AX) preceeded by "SUB SI, # 2  MOV 0 [SI], AX"
        (PUSH AX), and deletes both.  The second optimizer looks for
        "MOV BX, AX" preceeded by "MOV AX, # immediate", and changes the
        move immediate AX to a move immediate BX.  These two optimizers
        shortened the CLOCK program from about 5000 bytes down to 3800
        bytes.  The smallest .COM file I can now generate is 50 bytes,
        and the "Hello World!" program is 173 bytes, down from 330 bytes.

        Modified compiler so there are select words for specifying where
        words are going, rather than using special word names for each
        place. Specifically : (colon) and CODE are defered, and directed
        to either Forth, Target, or Library controlled by the words:

                >FORTH          >LIBRARY        >TARGET

        This makes the source code much easier to read, and much less
        error prone on entry.

 06/28/89

        Add automatic boot compiling to TCOM. Now it will initialize
        itself when it boots, and compile whatever file you put on the
        DOS command line. Here is an example of how to use TCOM:

                        TCOM CLOCK <enter>

                                or

                        TCOM SAMPLE <enter>

        You can keep TCOM from automatically starting to compile, with
        the following sequence:

                        TCOM CLOCK QUIT <enter>

        TCOM will open CLOCK.SEQ, but will QUIT before starting to
        compile it. You can then compile CLOCK by typing:

                        TARG <enter>

 06/28/89       ----

        Corrected the bug that was keeping me from starting to allocate
        data variables from address zero. The default flag for an
        unresolved symbol was zero (0), it has been changed to "-1".
        This should prevent further problems.

 07/07/89

        Extended the MOV_BX,AX optimizer to test for the additional case
        where this instruction is preceeded by MOV AX, 0 [SI]. If this
        is found, then the instruction is changed to MOV BX, 0 [SI].

        Added two additional optimizers. The first tests for the
        following case:


                DEC IP            ÄÄ¿
                DEC IP              ³     push item1 on the stack
                MOV 0 [SI], AX    ÄÄÙ
                MOV AX, 0 [SI]            get a copy of item one in AX

        This sequence can occur whenever we push "item1" on the stack
        and follow it with an operator that modifies item one
        subsequently returning it to the stack.  The optimization here
        is simply to discard the final instruction, saving two bytes and
        15 clock cycles.

        The second optimizer tests for multiple occurances of DROP in a
        program, and folds all multiple drops into a single inctruction
        "ADD SI, # xxxx" for the correct operation.

 07/13/89

        Factored the compiler to get as much of the target specific code
        out of it as possible. The target specific code has been moved
        into the library file.

        This is part of the process of modifying the compiler to work
        with additional target processors. I have coded a sample target
        that looks somewhat like a Forth Chip. It outputs assembly
        source at the moment that is re-directable to the printer. If
        you want to write a new target, you need only re-write the
        library file for the target processor. Of course this is only in
        theory for now.

 07/17/89

        Here is a list of command line parameters that can be passed to
        the target compiler. Also included is a description of their
        functions:

                /CODE           Display the assembled code as compiling
                /SRC            Display the source while compiling
                /OPT            Turn on the code optimizer
                /LST            Direct any output from the /CODE or /SRC
                                  options to IMAGE.LST.

        These options are used as follows:

                C> TCOM <filename> /CODE /SRC /OPT /LST <enter>

        They may be used in any order on the DOS command line.

 09/12/89

        Added help to display when TCOM is executed without any command
        line parameters. Here is the /HELP display:

      ÚÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ¿
      ³ Command line format:    "TCOM <filename> <option> <option> <...>"    ³
      ³ Command line compiler options available are:                         ³
      ³                                                                      ³
      ³ /code     = Enable the display of compiled code.                     ³
      ³ /codeoff  = Disable the display of compiled code ........ (default). ³
      ³ /src      = Enable the display of source while compiling.            ³
      ³ /srcoff   = Disable the display of source while compiling (default). ³
      ³ /opt      = Enable compiler optimization.                            ³
      ³ /optoff   = Disable compile optimization  ............... (default). ³
      ³ /lst      = Generate a listing file.                                 ³
      ³ /lstoff   = Don't generate a listing file ............... (default). ³
      ³ /sym      = Generate a symbol file for BXDEBUG.                      ³
      ³ /symoff   = Don't generate a symbol file ................ (default). ³
      ³ /DOS      = Shell out to DOS .......... (NOT a command line option). ³
      ³ /bye      = Return to DOS ............. (NOT a command line option). ³
      ³ /help     = Re-display this help text.                               ³
      ³                                                                      ³
      ³ Type /BYE to leave the compiler.                                     ³
      ÀÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÙ

 09/21/89

          Fixed VARIABLEs, CONSTANTS and ARRAYs so they return their
        proper value or address when they are used in interpret mode.
        This allows variables to be pre-initialized, and allows
        defined constants to be used in defining additional
        constants. This change also allowed me to get rid of the
        "L[']" word which was needed when variables were used in
        library code words.

          Modified compiler so it creates .COM, .SYM, and .LST files
        with the same name but different extensions as the file being
        compiled.

 09/30/89               **** Version .77 ****

          Modified entire LIBRARY to keep the top of stack in BX.
        This reduces the compiler output size, and improves code
        performance. All of the optimizers had to be re-written.
        Cleaned up some bugs in the way the optimizer flags were
        working, they were getting turned off, and not back on.
        FIXED. Added new flags /SHOW, and /SHOWOFF to control whether
        the application symbols were to be displayed as the compile
        was performed. The default is /SHOWOFF. /BYE can now be used
        on the command line to force the compiler to return to dos
        when the compile completes.

 09/03/89

          Added several optimizers, to improve the produced code. The
        most significant optimizer is IMM_OPT. It compresses in many
        cases 7 or 8 instructions into one instruction saving many
        clock cycles. The resulting code after optimization is now
        greater than 10% smaller. There are still problems with the
        listing file generated with the optimizer turned on, as many
        of the listing instructions are written, and subsequently
        discarded by the optimizer. I need to work on this, but I
        haven't yet figured out a good solution.

 10/06/89

          Improved string handling in libraries. You can now use " and
        ." in libraries. The strings are handled correctly, and no
        space in the target is allocated until the function containing
        the string is used in the target. You still must not use ," or
        CREATE in a library, as this will immediately allocate space
        and a symbol. Use ARRAY to specify an area of memory that will
        be needed by a library definition.

 10/10/89

          Added list file buffering to reduce the DOS overhead while
        creating a listing. Listings can be as much as 10 times the
        size of the original source files being compiled, so a 50k
        source file like the SZ editor, can create a listing file up to
        almost 500k bytes. If all you want is a listing of the symbols
        map, you can try the following command line options in the
        shown sequence: "TCOM <filename> /LST /SRCOFF /CODEOFF"

          The /LST turns on the source as well as the code output,
        alone with the symbol map at the listing end. following /LST
        with /SRCOFF and /CODEOFF leaves a listing file containing only
        the symbol map.

 10/11/89       **** Version .80 ****

          Changed the status of TCOM from Copyrighted to Public Domain
        this date.      Tom Zimmer

          Also added a new option to the compiler, /NOINIT. This
        option allows you to tell the compiler not to include the
        initialization code for console I/O. You can create smaller
        utilities with this option, but you cannot use TYPE, or SPACES.

 10/19/89

        Added a few new words to the system, cleaned up some problems
        associated with redefining words in the kernel. Added VALUE's,
        =:, !>, ABORT, ABORT", and MS. Added Peter Midnight's Towers of
        Hanoi solution to TCOM as another sample of an application you
        can target compile.

 10/23/89

        Added some simple graphics support for PLOT, POINT, LINE and
        LINETO. PLOT uses the BIOS, and as such is quite slow. You can
        use VMODE! to set whatever graphics mode you want. It is very
        simple, but it works with CGA, EGA, and VGA.

 10/24/89       **** Version .90 ****

        Added DEFER to the defining word set, thus allowing defered words
        to be used in a target compiled application. Use !>, =: or IS to
        store a function into a defered word.

 10/25/89

        Added support for:

                Pull down menus
                Framed boxes
                Screen save and restore

 10/26/89

        Got the previous entries functions reasonably debugged.

 10/29/89

        Added SAVE>, SAVE!> and RESTORE> to the compiler for variables
        and values. These are handy if you are trying to port applications
        to the target compiler from FPC.

 10/30/89

        Added LINEEDITOR to target library. This handy utility is used
        in many of my programs, and has proven indispensable.

        Fixed some bugs in ABORT", and added code to allow ABORT" to
        be used in a library routine. ABORT" will always do a BYE if
        an error occurs, so don't use it unless thats ok.

 11/01/89       **** Version 1.00 ****

        Modified the default initializaton, so more things are
        automatically initialized in the target. I spent a lot of time
        the other day trying to get an application to target compile
        only to find out my problems were caused by forgetting to
        initialize a utility that is automatically initialized in FPC,
        but wasn't in the target compiler. Sooo, I decided it was
        better to make larger target programs that work, than smaller
        target programs that don't work. You can always disable the
        default initialization with /NOINIT, and do your own, but the
        default should be to init.

 11/13/89

        Added the window file selection tool to TCOM, simply place the
        word GETFILE in your program when you want to pick a file from
        a list of files. Returns a1, the address of the selected file,
        and f1 true if a file was selected.

        Added SPINNER2. The two spinners show: left=lines compiled,
        and right=library colon definitions compiled.

        If the right spinner spins, and the left spinner stops, the
        compiler is compiling from the library rather than the disk.
        Spinners are turned off when output is directed to the listing
        file.

 11/15/89       ***** Version 1.01 *****

        Added Hypertext Help to the TCOM compiler. Just type TCOM <enter>
        then press the F1 key to invoke help.

 11/16/89       STDIO and IO redirection

        Added GETCHAR and PUTCHAR, the DOS redirectable I/O operators.
        GETCHAR returns a char unless the end of file has been reached.
        If the end of file is encountered, it returns a -1.

        The new function RAW_STDIN can be used at the start of a program
        to tell DOS to make STDIN "raw" and "unbuffered". Characters will
        be read one at a time rather than a line at a time as is normal
        for STDIN.

        Made KEY deferable, like TYPE. Added KEY-F a variable that gets
        initialized to hold %KEY which is a BDOS key that filters function
        keys and translates them, to greater than 127. KEY can be
        redirected to GETCHAR with STDIN_INIT for proper input redirection.

        Since the default I/O initialization DOSIO_INIT and the video
        version VMODE.SET both set KEY-F to %KEY, you must perform
        STDIN_INIT after one of these initialization words has been done
        to make it take effect.

 11/17/89

        Found a BUG in DEALLOC in the library. It was completely missing
        the MOV AH, # $49 instruction just before the INT $21. Added the
        afor mentioned instruction to fix.

        Reworked TSAVESCR and TWFL to ALLOC and DEALLOC the memory they
        need for operation. This makes thing cleaner, and removes the
        nest limit on saveing and restoring screens.

        Added TABLE and END-TABLE to the compiler, to be used for building
        tables of literal values in the target or in library functions.

ø11/20/89               ***** Version 1.02 *****

        Added ICODE and IMACRO to the defining word list. These words
        create CODE or MACRO type words that actually compile at target
        compiler build time rather than when they are referenced in the
        target. The object code is then moved into the target when
        needed. This saves both time and space in the compiler. One
        caution with ICODE and IMACRO words, they must not be used to
        define words that access external data, that is thry can't refer
        to BASE, or CAPS, or any other external to themselves variable or
        address. Since they are actually assembled when building the
        library, those variables won't exist yet so use CODE or MACRO if
        you need reference external data. ALSO these words are for use in
        the LIBRARY ONLY, there is no reason to use them in the actual
        target compiled application source code since that source is
        actually compiled at target time anyway. If you look at
        LIBRARY.SEQ, you will see many examples of how these words are
        used. They save about 4k in the target compiler, and make it
        about 10 percent faster.

 11/20/89

        Added simple hercules graphics support to TCOM. Mike Mayo obtained
        routines from Oliver Shank, and extracted and simplified the point
        plot routine for use with TCOM.

        Use GRAPH-INIT to initialize PLOT and POINT for COLOR or HERCULES,
        it returns TRUE if on a COLOR system, and FALSE for Hercules.
        Use this flag to select either HERCULES, or one of the COLOR
        graphics modes listed in TGRAPH.SEQ.

        The "VALUES" VDOTS, HDOTS and #COLORS are set according to the
        graphics mode selected.

 11/22/89

        Added LABEL to the set of defining words, it is currently ONLY
        available in the LIBRARY.

                ******************************************
                *** Not true any longer, see 03/27/90 ****
                ** LABEL can be used in the target code **
                ******************************************

        Added sample application LINES.SEQ to show how to make a program
        that will work in graphics mode on either CGA or HERCULES.

 11/23/89

        Removed the requirement that a "main" definition be added to the
        beginning of each target compilable file to set the entry point.
        TCOM NOW AUTOMATICALLY MAKES THE LAST DEFINITION IN YOUR FILE THE
        ENTRY POINT OF THE PROGRAM. Since this is normally the way Forth
        programs are written, transporting programs to TCOM should be a
        bit simpler. If you want to enter your program at a place other
        than what would normally be the last definition, you will need to
        add a definition to the end of your program to call your desired
        entry point.

        This change also makes it easier to make a program compilable on
        F-PC for debugging purposes since forward references are NO
        LONGER REQUIRED.

 11/23/89 10:39:54.67   ***** Version 1.03 *****

        This version was released to all attendees at the 1989 FORML
        conference at Asilimar, California. The conference occured
        between November 24th and 26th.

        *****************************************************************

 11/25/89

        Added "EXECUTES>" to the compiler. EXECUTES> allows target library
        words to have a specified FORTH vocabulary function they will
        execute when they are used in INTERPRET mode (as opposed to
        compiling) while target compiling.

        EXECUTES> is used as follows:

        MACRO TIB       ( -- a1 )       \ Terminal Input Buffer address
                        SAVE_BX
                        MOV BX, 'TIB    END-MACRO       EXECUTES> TIB

        Here we specify that the target TIB definition executes the
        FORTH TIB definition when in interpret mode. EXECUTES> looks up
        the word following in the FORTH vocabulary.

        The only limitation on EXECUTE>, is it may not be used after an
        ICODE or IMACRO library definition.

 11/27/89               ***** Version 1.04 *****

      ****************************************************************
      ******* The following ROMability has not yet been tested *******
      ****************************************************************

        Added some new command line options and code to allow TCOM to
        produce romable code as follows;

          /code-start   ( | <addr> -- )
                        Set target CODE starting address. Defaults to
                        $100, a DOS type program.

          /code-limit   ( | <addr> -- )
                        Set max size of CODE compiled into the target.
                        Defaults to $A000, which allows 40k of code and
                        24k of data in a compiled program.

          /data-start   ( | <addr> -- )
                        Set target data starting address. Normally zero,
                        but can be set to other values.

          /ram-start    ( | <seg> -- )
                        Set the segment in target memory where ram
                        is located, data is them moved into that ram from
                        the ROM.

          /ram-size     ( | <n1> -- )
                        set amount of ram available in the target.
                        Defaults to $FFEE if not specified.

        The /RAM-START segment defaults to $FFFF if not specified which
        signifies to the compiler that this is a RAM based system, which
        does not need to have its data moved from ROM to RAM.

        When compiling DOS type programs or utilities, the above
        parameters can usually be left with their default values.

        The /NOINIT option would of course need to be specified when
        compiling a ROMable application since much of the default
        initialization code deals with a DOS environment.

 11/28/89

        Finally fixed the branch distance limit. Conditional branches can
        now be as long as you want, you need only specify the command
        "LONG_BRANCH" either at the beginning of your source file, or
        before a definition that needs a longer branch than 127 bytes.
        The command "SHORT_BRANCH" switches back to 127 byte branch
        limits. The advantage of short branches, is they are faster and
        require less space.  The default is still SHORT.

        An additional pair of operators LONG_LIBRARY and SHORT_LIBRARY
        allow you to specify long or short branchs in the library files.
        Again the default is SHORT. Unless you add additional library
        functions that need long branches, short branches work for all
        library functions.

 11/29/89               ***** Version 1.05 *****

        Added TSHAPES.SEQ from Mike Mayo. This adds support for ARC and
        CIRCLE drawing. Small mod to TGRAPH, added "LINESET", to
        initialize line drawing so you can then use LINETO for successive
        segments to be drawn.

 12/05/89

        Modified line drawing some, renamed LINESET to be LINEFROM as in
        draw a LINE FROM point x, y. Modified LINE to reduce the number
        of stack operations needed. It is now defined interms of LINEFROM
        and LINETO. rather than the other way around.

        Added the read/write mode control from F-PC back into the target
        compiler. The new words available are:

                READ-ONLY   READ-WRITE   WRITE-ONLY   DEF-RWMODE

        The default HOPEN mode is READ-ONLY. If you use the sequence:

                READ-WRITE DEF-RWMODE

        at the beginning of your program, then all HOPEN's will be
        READ-WRITE.  HCREATE always makes files READ-WRITE which is the
        way they will stay until you HCLOSE and re-HOPEN them.

        Also needed to modify CARD.SEQ to make it select READ-WRITE for its
        BLOCK operations.

 12/12/89               ***** Version 1.06 *****

        Added 2VARIABLE, and 2CONSTANT to the defining words the compiler
        will recognize.

        Re-factored TARG_COMPILE to eliminate the large CASE statment,
        and instead use an EXEC: for speed. Changed the data types from
        literal 'LETTER' definitions, to an array of data types starting
        with the value 0.

 12/15/89

        Added full date/time and timer support from F-PC. New words
        include:

        HOURS           MINUTES         TENTHS          SECONDS
        10TH-ELAPSED    SEC-ELAPSED     .ELAPSED        B>SEC
        TIME-ELAPSED    TIME-RESET      B>T             T>B
        TTIME           STIME           .DATE           D.M.Y
        Y-M-D           M/D/Y           .TIME           DTBUF
        SETTIME         GETTIME         SETDATE         GETDATE

 12/18/89               ***** Version 1.07 *****

        Fixed a bug in EXHREAD and EXHWRITE. The word HDOS3 was broken,
        and was preventing these two wordds from working. Repaired.

        Added LINEREAD support, see the file TSREAD.SEQ for details.
        Some of the added words are:

            LINEREAD  LINEREAD_INIT  IBRESET  OUTBUF  LRHNDL

            LOADLINE .LRHNDL  MEMCHK  CURPOINTER  LINE_LIMIT

        Also added LOOK.SEQ an example of how to use the LINEREAD
        support just added.

 12/19/89

        Made some minor repairs to TPATH in the definition PATHSET, and
        added PATHSET back into HOPEN. Had to split THANDLES into two
        files to get TPATH to load without forward references.

 12/20/89

        Added a couple of words to library:

                $>TIB  ?LINE  ?CR  LMARGIN  RMARGIN  TABSIZE

        Adjusted automatic initialization to set LMARGIN to zero,
        RMARGIN to 64 and TABSIZE to 8.

 12/20/89               ****** Version 1.08 ******

        Just added Bob Smiths "Public Domain" high level floating point
        package to the target compiler. Preliminary testing indicates
        it is functioning properly. You can now use floating point
        functions in target compiled programs.

        The performance will probably not be up to Bob's SFLOAT package
        in F-PC, but shouldn't be too bad since the compiler generates
        call threaded assembly language. The file is TFLOAT.SEQ. It is
        not being included as a precompiled library, as it would add
        another 12k to the compiler. It is however defined as a library
        file, so if you FLOAD it at the start of your application, only
        the needed functions will actually be included in your program.
        Floating point space overhead will run from 4k to 10k depending
        on the functions used.

 12/21/89

        Found and fixed several bugs in the the TFLOAT.SEQ file, There
        were some stack problems that have been fixed.

 12/22/89               ***** Version 1.09 *****

        Split the first portion of LIBRARY.SEQ out to OPTIMIZ.SEQ to
        reduce its size some. It was over 100k.

        Changed MAXDIR in TWFL.SEQ from a constant to a value. You can
        now set MAXDIR to some value other than 300 to get the $GETDIR
        to get a different number of files than 300.

 01/02/90               ***** Version 1.10 *****

        Fixed a bug in LONG_BRANCHes, it seems the defered word T@ was
        not getting initialized to the target memory area, and when a
        long branch was being resolved with ">RESL", improper branch
        locations were being resolved.

        Added UPC, UPPER and ?UPPERCASE to the library word list.

        Renamed ADJ_MEMORY to SET_MEMORY, and changed the function from
        a segment adjustment of memory, to a byte adjustment of memory.
        It now is used to reduce DOS memory usage to a user specified
        amount of ram above PAD. The physical memory address is passed
        into SET_MEMORY. Typically you will do something like the
        following:
                        PAD 100 + SET_MEMORY

        This will reduce the DOS memory usage from "all of memory" down
        to the memory needed for the programs CODE plus DS: ram upto
        PAD+100. The return stack and TIB are automatically moved down
        to the new location, and the data stack is cleared. An additional
        250 bytes are allocated for the data stack and the return stack.

 01/04/90               ***** Version 1.11 *****

        Fixed EXECUTES> so it will always assemble the two instructions
        it needs to assembler, into the Forth CODE space, not the target
        space.

        Mostly working on making the floating point useful. Needed to
        be able to enter floating point numbers at interpret time so
        new floating point constants and arrays could be created by a
        target application. So now TFLOAT will load FLOAT4TH before
        loading itself. FLOAT4TH gets loaded into the FORTH vocabulary
        so it can be used to manipulate floating point numbers while
        target compiling.

        Added the floating point wordset description to the LIBRARY.DOC
        file. They are in a different format from the rest of the
        glossary, but still provide useful information.

 01/05/90

        Enhanced PERFORM, and EXECUTE so they compile a single
        instruction when the optimizer is enabled. This resulted in an
        improvement in performance for DEFERed words, allowing me to
        get rid of the I/O variables KEY-F, EMIT-F, TYPE-F and
        SPACES-F that were used in the colon definitions of KEY, EMIT,
        TYPE and SPACES. These words were then converted to DEFERed
        words, which subsequently compile a single instruction. Overall
        this results in an improvement in performance with a very small
        target program size increase.

        Making KEY, EMIT, and TYPE defered words also improves code
        compatibility with F-PC.

 01/06/90

        Added "@>" to the list of forward words at the end of
        COMPILER.SEQ. Apperently I just forgot it when I made the list
        of forward words. It can be used on VALUE's, VARIABLE's, and
        DEFERed words.

        NOTE:  You CANNOT use ['] on DEFERed words, as they are not
        accessed with a CALL. DEFERed words are treated like MACRO's.
        The ['] function in the target compiler is a RUNTIME operation,
        that is, it obtains the "CFA" of the function following at
        runtime, by looking following itself at the address in the CALL
        following. For ['] to work properly, it can ONLY be followed by
        a Forth word that is NOT A MACRO.

        Added a test for end of file reached while compiling. If you
        forget to terminate a definition with a ";", then TCOM will
        abort with a message informing you that the end of file has
        been reached while compiling.

01/08/90                ***** Version 1.12 *****

      ÉÍÍÍÍÍ» THE FOLLOWING NOTE IS INVALID, SEE NOTE ù03/26/90 ÉÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ»
      º     ÈÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ¼       º
      º                                                                 º
      º Added user created defining words to the target compiler. the   º
      º format is somewhat different from the normal F-83/F-PC type     º
      º defining words, but provides similar functionality. Here are a  º
      º couple of examples of how to add defining words to the target   º
      º program:                                                        º
      º                                                                 º
      º          \ at runtime, new definitions return addr              º
      º :DOES> ; ( -- a1 )                                              º
      º                                                                 º
      º DEF: NEWARRAY   ( n1 -- ) CREATE ALLOT ;                        º
      º                                                                 º
      º 25 NEWARRAY ARRAY1                                              º
      º                                                                 º
      º As you can see the DOES> portion is defined first. This is      º
      º somewhat similar to a technique Bill Ragsdale proposed a few    º
      º years ago. It make the target compile process simpler. The      º
      º ":DOES>" word defines the runtime function of the words the new º
      º defining word will make. The "DEF:" word defines a new defining º
      º word, and specifies what the compile time operations will be    º
      º for the new defining word. In this case we are creating a new   º
      º array word, which will do a CREATE, and ALLOT some space in the º
      º target for data. The runtime function of the new "ARRAY1"       º
      º simply returns the address of the array on the stack.           º
      º                                                                 º
      º            \ at runtime, new definitions return contents        º
      º :DOES> @ ; ( -- n1 )                                            º
      º                                                                 º
      º DEF: NEWCONSTANT ( n1 -- ) CREATE , ;                           º
      º                                                                 º
      º 52 NEWCONSTANT MYCONSTANT                                       º
      º                                                                 º
      º Here we are creating a new defining word that is like CONSTANT, º
      º at compile time it creates the new name "MYCONSTANT" and        º
      º comma's 52 into the target data space. At runtime, MYCONSTANT   º
      º will fetch the data and return it.                              º
      º                                                                 º
      ÈÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ¼

        P.S. DON'T try to ['] a target defining word and step into the
        body of the definition, you will get unexpected results. It is
        legal to ['] a definition for storage into a defered word.


        Added TIMER.SEQ to the group of sample programs.

 01/16/90               ***** Version 1.13 *****

        Split out the STDIO words into a new file called TSTDIO.SEQ.
        Also added several new buffered STDIO words as follows:

        GCH.MAX         Maximum read characters to buffer.
        PCH.MAX         Maximum write characters to buffer.
        BUFIO_INIT      Initialize buffered I/O for use.
        GETCHAR_B       Read one character from buffered I/O console.
        PUTCHAR_B       Write one character to the buffered I/O channel.
        FLUSH_B         Flush the buffered I/O channel before leaving.

        Buffered I/O must be initialized with BUFIO_INIT before using
        either GETCHAR_B or PUTCHAR_B. The word FLUSH_B must be used
        before returning to DOS, to flush any character not already
        written.

        Performance is significantly affected by the size of the read
        and write buffers. The default size of 32 bytes works well, but
        a considerable improvement in throughput can be obtained by
        increasing GCH.MAX and or PCH.MAX to around 2000.  This will of
        course use more DS: memory.

        Also added the FILTER.SEQ example.

 01/18/90

        Generalized the symbol table generation words. The /SYM option
        can be used to tell TCOM to build a .SYM file for your
        debugger. The only debugger currently supported is BXDEBUG.
        Three words have been added to allow a symbol table file to be
        built for other debuggers, but you will need to know the
        format of their symbol table. The words are SYMWRITE,
        SYMHEADER, and SYMFOOTER. Look at the COMPILER.SEQ for an
        example.

 01/19/90

        Added RS232IB.SEQ a buffered RS232 driver to the TCOM.ZIP
        file. RS232IB.SEQ provides a serial driver that is compatible
        with both F-PC and TCOM, you can load it on either one and use
        it directly. RS232IB.SEQ is not a library file, but is a simple
        terminal program with the serial driver included.

 01/22/90               ***** Version 1.14 *****

        Added another command line option. Since TCOM normally contains
        the full F-PC Forth system, including the SED editor, it seemed
        only natural to add an edit command line parameter. Start TCOM
        in edit mode as follows:

                TCOM /EDIT <filename> <enter>

        TCOM will open the file if it already exists, or open it as a
        NEWFILE if it doesn't exist. Leaving the editor, will then
        return to DOS after saving changes. "/E" is short for "/EDIT".

        TCOM is still not a full compiler environment like TurboC, but
        it is getting closer.

 01/24/90               ***** Version 1.15 *****

        Integrated Bob Smiths new (1.2) version of FLOAT4TH into TCOM.

 01/29/90

        The compiler now returns a DOS errorlevel code that corresponds
        to the number of errors encountered while compiling.

        A /QUIET of /Q option can be used to reduce the junk displayed
        while compiling to errors only. When used with the DOS
        ">filename" option on the commandline, an error file will be
        built that can be scanned by an editor for compile error
        locations to fix. In other words, I am in the process of
        modifying the Z editor to use it as a compiler integrator, and
        I needed a way to pass errors back to the editor from the
        compiler. These options provide a way to do that. Here is an
        example:

                C:>TCOM TEST /Q >TEST.TMP

        Here the compiler will compile the file TEST, and re-direct the
        compilers message output to the file TEST.TMP.

 01/31/90               ***** Version 1.16 *****

        Added ZZ (I don't know what it stands for) to TCOM. ZZ is the
        first version of an integrator for TCOM. Is uses the SZ editor,
        TCOM.EXE and BXDEBUG as sub programs to provide an environment
        that can create, compile and debug programs. Some additional
        keys and functions have been added to the SZ editor to make
        this work. SZ has a new command line option "/CMD" that will
        tell SZ to automatically examine a <filename>.MSG file when
        atarting up to look for error messages in the Microsoft C error
        format. If the file containing valid error messages is found,
        then SZ will automatically place the cursor on the error line
        and display the error message on the last line of the display.
        When the SZ editor leaves, a file ZZ.CMD will be created that
        contains information that the Mini Shell will look at to decide
        what to do next. ZZ will look at a file ZZ.CFG that will
        contain DOS command lines to perform. The first line will be
        executed when ZZ starts, and other lines will be executed
        according to the command (an ascii character 1 to 9, or Q)
        passed back from the SZ editor. Multiple commands on a line in
        ZZ.CFG can be entered separated by the ";" character.

        All this may seem complicated, so here is an overview:

                Type ZZ <filename>.SEQ <enter> to start editing a file.

                Press F5 to compile the file.

                If an error occurs, the editor will display errors.

                Press ESC to get out of error mode or press Ctrl-F2 to
                execute the compiled program.

                Press F7 to enter BXDEBUG on your file, or press F10 to
                leave SZ.

        Here is a list of the keys in SZ that pass back commands to ZZ.

                F10                     command Q
                Alt-F10                 command Q
                Ctrl-F1 or Alt-1        command 1
                Ctrl-F2    Alt-2        command 2
                Ctrl-F3    Alt-3        command 3
                Ctrl-F4    Alt-4        command 4
                F5         Alt-5        command 5
                           Alt-6        command 6
                F7         Alt-7        command 7
                           Alt-8        command 8
                           Alt-9        command 9
                           Alt-0        command 10

        These commands are used by ZZ to make it perform ZZ.CFG lines 2
        through 11.

        Commands can be separated by the ';' character, and if you
        place a double '||' vertical bar then the rest of the line can
        be used for comments. Here are a couple of examples:

                CLS|BXDEBUG %F.com||        F7=Debug program "COMMENT"

        The above sequence will, CLS the screen, and execute BXDEBUG,
        passing it the parameter "%F.com" that is the same as "%1",
        except ZZ removes the file extention so you can specify it
        ".com". The "||" two vertical bars signify the end of the
        command, and the remaining text on the line is treated as
        comments.

        When you leave and re-enter ZZ, and don't specify a file to
        edit, as in "ZZ <enter>", then ZZ will remember where you were,
        and return to that file and edit position.

 02/05/90

        Switched to modified versions of TGRAPH.SEQ, and THERC.SEQ.
        Added THERCTXT.SEQ to TCOM. Jerry Modrow cleaned them up a bit,
        and provided code to do text output in Hercules graphics mode.
        The code was written by Mike Mayo, and generalized by Jerry
        Modrow. Also added GRAPH.SEQ, and HERC.SEQ to allow for
        comparable simple graphics in F-PC for debugging purposes. The
        graphics available from SMILEY, is faster, but GRAPH and HERC
        are compatible with TGRAPH, and THERC.

 02/22/90               ***** Version 1.17 *****

        Changed the default return-stack/TIB size "RPSIZE" from 240
        bytes to 256 bytes.

        Modified ZZ, to handle upto four parameters on the command
        line. I am currently only using three. The order of the
        parameters in the ZZ.CMD file has been changed to match the
        order of the same parameters on the command line, that is:

                <filename> <row> <col>

        Rather than the previous:

                <row> <col> <filename>

        This makes more sense, and allows me to increase the total
        number of parameters that can be handled to four so people with
        other editors can generate command files with upto four
        parameters in the same order as they accept parameters.

        Im still working on a way to document ZZ so it will be easy to
        understand what it does. Currently the inter-connection between
        ZZ and the programs it integrates is quite obscure, and I don't
        know if anyone can figure out how to use ZZ with only what I am
        providing. Need to work on this a LOT MORE.

 03/07/90               ***** Version 1.18 *****

        Added DIS.SEQ and DIS.COM to TCOM.ZIP. While this may seem like
        a silly reason to change the version number, DIS adds important
        functionality to TCOM. DIS will disassemble any .COM file that
        was created by TCOM that has a .SYM file available, into a
        symbolic assembly listing file. It only disassembles the CODE
        portion of the .COM file, but it seems to do that perfectly.
        Now you can easily see the difference between optimized and
        non-optimized compiler output. The DOS ">" symbol can be used
        to force redirection into a file as follows:

                DIS CLOCK >CLOCK.LST

        This will disassemble CLOCK.COM (with symbols if CLOCK.SYM is
        available, and with imbeded source if CLOCK.LIN and CLOCK.SEQ
        are available.) to the file CLOCK.LST. The .SYM and .LIN files
        are created by TCOM when the /SYM command line option is used.
        If no redirection is used, disassembly is directed to the
        display.

        DIS can be used to disassemble .COM files that don't have .SYM
        files, or .COM file from other assemblers of compilers, but it
        will not properly know how much to disassemble, and will not
        display symbols.

 03/08/90

        Added CASE, OF, ENDOF, ENDCASE in the F-PC style. Like Eakers
        CASE.  I got tired of converting programs that use CASE
        statments over to use IF-ENDIF, so I added the CASE statment to
        the compiler. It has been tested, and when the optimizer is
        turned on, it generates very good code.

 03/19/90               ***** Version 1.19 *****

        Started modifications to generalize TCOM for a new target. Mike
        Mayo has finished the first pass on an 80196 assembler. Some
        changes were needed (more will be needed) to work with this new
        target. I am looking forward to this new addition to TCOM, it
        should add considerable flexibility to the compiler.

 03/23/90               ***** Version 1.20 *****

        Many small changes. Adjusted TYPE, EMIT, CR, SPACES, AT, AT?
        to be more like F-PC. Several were made into defered words.
        This will cause the compiler output to increase in size
        somewhat for small programs. This is unfortunate, but
        necessary for better compatibility.

        Fixed a couple of bugs, the small version of the compiler
        couldn't create proper listing files because I was removing too
        much from SF-PC for the disassembler to load. CORRECTED

        Made corrections to TGRAPH for CPLOT. It needed to be clearing
        BX before performing the plot interrupt.

ø03/26/90

        Re-worked defining words. You can now create ordinary CREATE
        DOES> type defining words, you simply start the definition with
        "::" rather than ":". The compiler will only include the DOES>
        portion in your target, and will execute the part before DOES>
        whenever the defining word is used to define a new target word.
        Here is a simple example of a TCOM defining word:

                :: 6VAR         ( | <name> -- )
                                CREATE 0 , 0 , 0 , DOES> ;

                6VAR MYVARIABLE
                6VAR YOURVARIABLE

        6VAR is a defining word that creates new 6 byte variables. 6VAR
        is being used to create two such variables called MYVARIABLE,
        and YOURVARIABLE. When these variables are later used, they
        will return the address of a 6 byte data area that was
        pre-initialized to zero.

 03/27/90

        Added the definition for Target LABEL, you can now use labels
        in the target code. They can be accessed from within a code
        word with a CALL. When used labels return their address.

 03/28/90

        Removed THERC.SEQ, TGRAPH.SEQ, & TSHAPES.SEQ from the
        precompiled library. You will need to "NEEDS" or "FLOAD" them
        into an application that requires graphics support. This makes
        the compiler about 7k smaller. The reason this is being done
        now, is that LABEL which is used in THERC was only available as
        a LIBRARY word before yesterday.

 03/28/90               ***** Version 1.21 *****

        Made ['] smart, so it tests for the type of word being looked
        up. The word must be a subroutine, or ['] will complain. The
        purpose here is to prevent looking up macros, which get
        compiled in line, and have no actual target address.

 03/29/90

        Modified typed output from a TCOM application so you can use
        PRINTING ON to cause typed output to go to the printer. This
        works with both DOS output, and the video typed output.

 03/30/90

        Added INLINE to TCOM. INLINE forces a routine that is normally
        accessed by a CALL to be compiled inline in the current colon
        definition. This avoids the overhead of a CALL RET in areas
        that need the highest performance. The generated code will of
        course be larger.

        Also added NO_INLINE to abort an inline operation if a LIBRARY
        word with multiple exits is preceeded by the INLINE directive.
        See the LIBRARY.SEQ definition of UM/MOD for an example.

        Added code to prevent INLINE from trying to compile a target
        (as opposed to LIBRARY) word inline.

 03/31/90

        Added colon definition MACROS to TCOM. Use "M:" to define colon
        definitions you want to always be compiled inline when they are
        referenced.

 04/03/90               ***** Version 1.22 *****

        Added CSEG, DSEG, END-CSEG, and END-DSEG to create multiple
        code segment areas. This is useful for target processors that
        need to compile code or data into specific areas of their
        memory. CSEG is used as follows:

                $1000 CSEG MY_PROGRAM
                $FFF0 CSEG VECTOR_SEG

                MY_PROGRAM              \ select the code segment
                                        \ starting at $1000
                <your code goes here>

                VECTOR_SEG              \ select the vector segment
                                        \ area

                xx , xx , xx , xx , xx , xx , xx , xx ,

                MY_PROGRAM              \ switch baack to MY_SEGMENT

                <more code goes here>

                END-CSEG                \ completes MY_PROGRAM segment
                                        \ in preperation for saving the
                                        \ image to disk.

        As in the CODE example above, the words DSEG and END-DSEG are
        used to create, select and end a DATA segment of the target.

 04/09/90

        Made a minor modification to TFLOAT.SEQ and FLOAT4TH.SEQ. They
        now return a 1 rather than -1 for conversion successful. It
        seems SFLOAT returns a 1 for successful, and -1 for double
        number conversion. This was causing Jerry's MANDEL program to
        underflow the stack when the number entered was convertable to
        a double number. For example SFLOAT will convert "1.0" as a
        double number rather than a floating point number since there
        is no "E" to signal a floating point conversion. Applications
        that want to be compatible with both AFLOAT and FLOAT4TH, need
        to use the following conversion code when using "(FNUMBER?)":

                : #INPUT        ( | <number> -- floating# )
                                BL WORD (FNUMBER?) DUP 0=
                                ABORT" Bad floating point number"
                                0<
                                IF      FLOAT   \ convert double to
                                                \ float
                                THEN    ;

 04/10/90

        Enhanced DUMP in the library, it now displays 16 bytes of hex
        data, followed by 16 bytes of ascii characters per line. Also
        added LDUMP to the library.

 04/11/90

        Added the value ABORT_FUNC and modified ABORT, such that, if
        ABORT_FUNC is non-zero, then it is executed. If it is zero,
        then a BYE is performed.

        Fixed COMPARE, and the sub functions COMP and CAPS-COMP so they
        use SSEG to determine what segment is being used for the
        compare.

 04/12/90               ***** Version 1.23 *****

        Added the ability to create an interpretive Forth system on top
        of your application program with the "/FORTH" command-line
        option. When this option is specified, TCOM will load a file
        called TFORTH.SEQ on top of your application, which adds a
        Forth like interactive shell, and about 8k bytes to your
        application. When your program is then executed, it will come
        up in the Forth shell, rather than your program. You can then
        execute words, dump memory and more interactively test your
        program than with the fully optimized .COM file. You cannot
        however define any new words, as there is no compiler included
        in this interpretive environment.

 04/13/90

        Fixed a bug in TFLOAT.SEQ and FLOAT4TH.SEQ. The number output
        routine was not shifting the mantissa properly. Corrected.

 04/14/90

        Added /DIS option, when used with the /FORTH option, also
        appends the disassembler to your application. This allows you
        to use SEE and DIS (in assembly language) to examine your
        routines while in the interpretive environment.

 04/17/90               ***** Version 1.24 *****

        Added a target compiled version of CODEBUG to TCOM, called
        TDEBUG.SEQ. The compiler option /DEBUG will force inclusion of
        ALL interpretive options, Forth, DIS, and DEBUGing. It is now
        possible to make programs that include a built in debugger. The
        overhead for the interpretive environment, with disassembly and
        debugger, is around 21k optimized, and 27k non-optimized. While
        this is not an insignificant amount, it does allow debugging.
        The commands available are TRACE <name>, and BREAKAT <name>.

 04/18/90

        Modified the .SYM file format, so it marks the most significant
        bit of the first letter of each subroutine name. This is done
        when the /FORTH command line option is used, and allows the
        interpretive environment to know which words are to be executed
        rather than returned as an address. Since this change is not
        compatible with the BXDEBUG debugger, the /SYM option when used
        without /FORTH will create a normal .SYM file usable with
        BXDEBUG.

 04/19/90

        Added environment string processing to TCOM. If you add a
        statment to your environment similar to the following;

                SET PATH= /OPT /NOINIT

        TCOM will default to using optimization, and no initialization
        when it compiles an application file. This environment string
        can be upto 250 characters in length, and is interpreted BEFORE
        the command line options are interpreted. This means your
        environment selections can be overridden by command line
        options if desired.

        Also added a default PATH to TCOM from the environment. You can
        add an additional statment to your environment as follows;

                SET TPATH=C:\FPC\TCOM

        TCOM will search for any source libraries or source files in the
        specified directory or directories, allowing TCOM to be used
        from other directories on your hard disk.

 04/23/90

        Added PROMPTER.SEQ as an additional example program. It prompts
        for user input, and passes that input off with a DOS shell to
        another program. It is an example of how to get user input, and
        how to shell out to DOS.

 04/24/90

        Added a couple of new functions to the library. #INPUT will
        wait for the user to enter an integer, and return it. TIB0
        holds the reset address of 'TIB. QUIT is TFORTH.SEQ has been
        modified to reset 'TIB at its start. SET_MEMORY has been
        modified to readjust 'TIB which it didn't do before. It MUST do
        this when resetting the stacks.

        Added TPAS.SEQ an updated version of my Pascal compiler, and
        PASX.PAS a sample pascal source file for TPAS to translate into
        Forth. See TPAS.SEQ for more information.

 04/25/90               ***** Version 1.25 *****

        Substantialy reorganized TCOM's files into a more workable
        form. TCOM.Zip now contains several other .ZIP files containing
        things like the source for TCOM, the utilities for TCOM, and
        the example file for TCOM. I have created a documentation file
        specific for each .Zip file. I think it is just about time to
        make an installation program for TCOM.

        Removed all references to HIDE and REVEAL from COMPILER.SEQ.
        Since TCOM doesn't allow redefinition of functions, all headers
        are created findable. This makes recursive operations easy,
        and eliminates a bug caused by HIDE when it is used in any word
        that built a header. Since the header to be built may already
        exist, then the word like ":" trying to make the ehader checks
        for this condition, and just resolves the name if a forward
        reference condition exists. Unfortunately HIDE went ahead and
        hid the most recent header created, NOT A GOOD IDEA!.

 04/26/90

        Today I re-factored TCOM again, It now consists of five .ZIP
        files as follows:

                TCOM        The executable with documentation
                TCOMSAMP    Sample TCOMable program examples
                TCOMUTIL    Utilities, and more library functions
                TCOMSRC     The source for TCOM, usable with F-PC 3.50
                SMALTCOM    Files to build a small TCOM compiler

        Also coded up and tested TCOMINST.COM an installation program
        for TCOM compiled with TCOM. Similar to INSTALL.EXE for F-PC,
        it allows the user to specify the target drive and directory.
        TCOM is getting more friendly all the time.

 04/27/90

        Received and integrated the bug fixes today from Bob Smith on
        FLOAT4TH and TFLOAT to F< F> FMIN and FMAX. Preliminary tests
        indicate they work properly.

 05/09/90

        Completed first pass prototype of the 8080 target for TCOM. It
        doesn't work yet, but the assembler seems to work. The
        assembler for now at least has been left as POSTFIX ONLY, as
        has the 8080 kernel.

 05/10/90

        Added START-T: to the list of defered words that needs to be
        implemented for a new target. In the 8086 target, this word is
        defined as a NOOP. In the 8080 target where we are generating
        indirect threaded code, this word compiles into the current
        target here, a word that is passed on the stack. For CODE type
        words, that would be a pointer to HERE+2, for colon type words,
        a pointer to NEST.

        Also added a defered word COMP_HEADER that compiles a header
        into the target. COMP_HEADER is passed an address counted
        string of the name to compile into the target. Two compile
        flags added /HEADER and /NOHEAD (default) select wheather
        headers are to be built for a particular target processor.

        Still have lots of work to do on the 8080 target, before it
        will generate real programs, but it has at least been able to
        compile through a very simple program, and generate what
        appears to be reasonable code. Its a start!

        I notice we are coming up on a whole year of work on TCOM. It
        is amazing what can be done in a year.

 05/11/90

        Added "RESOLVE_1" as a defered word to be used in resolving
        forward references. The default version resolves forward
        references as relative, and the 8080 version needed absolute
        addressing, so this was added.

 05/14/90               ***** Version 1.26 *****

        More minor modifications to allow TCOM to work with the 8080
        indirect threaded kernel. I keep finding things that are CALL
        threaded specific. The 8080 target is comming along very well,
        I have not been able to "run test" any code yet, but the manual
        disassemblies look very good.

        fixed some more bugs in the branch resolution words in
        LABEL80.SEQ. I believe branches are now working properly
        (again?). Added the compiler words to perform ." and " for the
        8080 target, these are in LIB80.SEQ.

 05/16/90

        Defered the DOES> portion of FOR>WORD so it can work properly
        with the 8080 indirect threaded target.

 07/03/90

        Added ALLSPECS.SEQ. A utility that is usable on either TCOM or
        F-PC that will return a list of all directories on a drive.
        Useful for searching an entire drive for things. Currently
        being used in LOOK.COM to allow a string search of an entire
        drive. Also used in the NEWZ editor, to allow hyper indexing an
        entire disk drive.

 07/09/90           **** 8086 Target Version 2.01 *****

        Changed a few of the "M:" words back to ":" words. Things like
        SPACE and some others are used too oftain to have them compiled
        inline as macros. This of course highly subjective, but it
        seemed like a proper change to make.

        Also fixed a bug in DIS.SEQ, it seems I added a word SPACE
        after an "EXEC:" in ".DISP". Not a good idea. Also modified DIS
        so it will only stop disassembling a file for which it has no
        symbol table when the end of the file is reached, or when the
        user stops it.

 07/24/90

        Added two words to the compiler to verify the state of the
        default code inclusion. CHECK_/NOINIT and CHECK_/DEFINIT These
        words will check to make sure their respective option is
        currently active, and will issue an error message but continue
        compiling if the option is not active. Use these near the start
        of a file that needs to always have one of the ..INIT options
        set a specific way.

 10/28/90           ***** Version 1.27 *****

        Added SKIP'C' to TDEFINED in the compiler, is was converting
        lowercase 'a' type letters to uppercase when it shouldn't.
        Also bumped version.

        Also added a verify section to TDEFINED, that makes sure that
        any words found are above the forth kernel, to make sure no
        invalid words get used in the target. This will improve the
        reliability of the generated code.

 10/29/90       **** 8086 Target Version 2.02 *****

        Added CRLF>BL'S to LIBRARY.SEQ. A very useful word when dealing
        with lines read from a file.

        Added ?DEF.EXE & DEFEXT to THANDLES.SEQ. The default extension
        is NONE, but you can now specify a default file extension if
        you want to, just by putting it in DEFEXT.

        I have separated out the Hyper-text compiler from the editor,
        and turned it into a separate TCOM application. This will (when
        I remove the old code from the editor) make the editor somewhat
        smaller. You can still SHELL out to run the indexer, if you
        want to. It is now called INDEX.COM, and will by default use
        INDEX.CFG for the compile specification if no other filename is
        specified on the command line after INDEX.

        Enhanced the DIS (disassembler), to include a new command line
        option. "/Wxx" where xx is a number of pages will disassemble
        the specified file in "Wide" mode for xx pages. If xx is
        omitted, then all pages will be disassembled. An escape
        sequence is also sent at the beginning of the output to put a
        laser printer in compressed mode. With this option, you can
        disassemble directly to a laser printer as follows:

                DIS [filename] /W2 [wordname] >PRN [enter]

        This command line will disassemble [filename] starting at
        [wordname] for 2 pages, with output directed to the PRN device,
        typically your printer.

 12/14/90            ***** Version 1.28 *****
                **** 8086 Target Version 2.03 ****

        Added &> to the compiler, it puts the address of a VALUE on the
        stack. Useful when you may have a series of values that you
        want to work with as a group.

        Added BLINK_OFF and BLINK_ON to TVIDEO.SEQ. This allows the
        colors from 8 to 15 to be used in the background without
        causing the screen to blink.

        Added ZLIST.SEQ to TCOMSAMP.ZIP. ZLIST allows viewing files in a
        similar fashion to Buerg's LIST, with fewer features, but it is
        fully public domain, and can be used by anyone for anything.
        Allows viewing BIIIGG files. You also get the source of course.

 01/28/91         ***** Version 1.30 *****
                **** 8086 Target Version 2.04 ****

        Fixed a couple of bugs in the CSEG/DSEG code, It was nessecary
        that you create a CSEG statment and use the CSEG name created,
        and then use END-CSEG at the end of your code. All this was
        needed to get it to save your compiled code is HEXSAVE was used
        to save the compilers output in INTEL HEX format. This has been
        fixed, such that a default segment is specified by the compiler
        initialization code in the optimizer file, and an end-cseg /
        end-dseg is performed automatically when the compile is
        finished.

        Two new directives have been added, ORG, and DORG. They allow
        specification of a new code or data origin, without having to
        specify a name for the new segment. This is much more like
        traditional assemblers, and allows you to freely move the code
        compiling around as desired. NOTE HOWEVER THAT TCOM PERFORMS NO
        OVERLAP CHECKING, and code compiled later can easily overlap
        code compiled earlier if these words are used haphazardly.

        Named segments are of course still allowed, making it possible to
        switch back and forth between existing segments. When ORG is
        used, it is not possible to switch back to a previous ORG, since
        no name available.

 01/28/91 17:36

        Added the ability in CODE words in the target to branch to and
        define named labels, both forward and backward. They are used as
        follows:

                code x1
                        jmp x2          \ forward branch to undefined
                                        \ label or code is now legal
                        jmp x3
                        ret             end-code

                code x2
                        jne x1
                label x3                \ code words can now contain
                                        \ label definitions
                        jmp x3
                        ret             end-code

        If you enter a forward branch to a label that is never defined,
        then an undefined symbol error will occur. You can also see a
        branch out of range error for labels that get defined too far
        away. The "WORD" instruction modifier will fix this problem for
        those instructions that allow word length branching.

 02/06/91               ***** Version 1.31 *****

        Modified the memory management in TCOM to use the new memory
        management technique just installed in F-PC. That is to use
        POINTER to define a word that will return a physical segment at
        runtime of the desired area of memory rather than using ALLOC.
        The primary advantage of this, is now F-PC internally uses only
        one segment pointer, and performs the heap management itself,
        adjusting its segment as needed for each new pointer used. At a
        later time, it will now be possible to move some or all
        "pointers" into expanded memory.


 02/06/91               ***** Version 1.32 *****

        Changed to compile order of TCOM to move ALIST.SEQ to after the
        compiler, so some additional "listing format" specific words
        could be moved into ALIST.SEQ.  ALIST is still an optional file,
        and need not be loaded if no listing capability is needed.

        TCOM is now much more flexable in allowing the target to define
        the listing format than before. Added defered words ?.MACRO and
        ?.CALL so ALIST.SEQ can define the format of the listing file
        format.

 02/20/91               ***** Version 1.33 *****

        Fixed bug in END-DSEG that was preventing proper functioning of
        the hex save.

        Modified ORG to set LINESTRT.

        Modified the way the compiler detects the /CODE command line
        option. It used to test the defered word .INST to see if it was
        set to a function other than NOOP. This is clumsy, and now the
        compiler variable ?CODE has been added, and returns a true if we
        are displaying the disassembled code/instructions while
        compiling.

        Added the defered word TARGET-FINISH to allow a target to perform
        any cleanup it desires after the compile is completed, but before
        the image save is performed.

 03/07/91        **** 8086 Target Version 2.05 ****

        Fixed a bug in the design on "EXEC:" which was patching the
        application code at runtime to vector to the desired function
        (self-modifying code).  Now it is probably a littel slower, but
        it should work on higher level processors with pipe-lines and
        caches.

 03/13/91        **** 8086 Target Version 2.06 ****

        Fixed a bug in -SKIP, changed an INC CX to DEC CX.

 03/19/91

        Fixed a bug in LABEL. The new version of label was not usable
        outside of a CODE word. It didn't install TINTERP like CODE did,
        so END-CODE would crash after reinstalling the null in the value
        INTERPSAVE. Things have been fixed now, so LABEL can be used
        outside of a CODE word, and infact really calls CODE in this
        case.  The purpose of using LABEL outside of a CODE word, was to
        make a code sequence that could return its address rather than
        executing like a CODE word does when used. In TCOM, CODE and
        LABEL both return their address when used in another code word.

 03/21/91       ***** TCOM Version 1.34 *****

        Factored the way TCOM compiles data statments like " or ."
        strings. In a target that generates romable code, data statments
        need to be in the CODE area since ram is not initialized in a rom
        program like it is in the 8086 PC .COM programs. To do this I
        have created a new set of "ORG" words with the "V" prefix (like
        VORG, VSEG, and END-VSEG), and changed the "D" org words to
        defered words.  This allows the 8086 TCOM to continue to assume
        data will be compiled into DATA space, and to allow ROM targets
        to use "V" words for variables, and have the "D" words compile
        into CODE/ROM space.  The way you switch between these two forms,
        is with "/DATA_IN_ROM" and "/DATA_IN_RAM".  When data is in ram,
        then you use only the ORG and DORG words. When data is in rom,
        then you also use VORG to specify where the variables will start.

 03/22/91

        Changed the automatic local label branch assign word BR# so it
        returns the number of the most recent branch number assigned,
        rather than the next available number.  BR# used to be a VALUE,
        it is now a function, and the VALUE BR#VAL has been created to
        take its place.

        Also added /DATA_IN_CODE, to allow placement of string inline
        with the code being generated.

 04/24/91

        Modified @-T and C@-T to be defered words in COMPILER.SEQ.

 04/25/91       ***** Compiler Version 1.35 *****

        Made ," (comma quote) defered, so a target can make it compile
        into some place other than data space. Modified COMPILER.SEQ

 05/13/91

        Adjusted the file write functions for /LST, /SYM and /LIN to use
        POINTER type buffers, reducing the CODE memory overhead for the
        compiler.  Also allows larget buffers to be used improving
        compiler performance.

 05/16/91

        Modified the compiler to work with the new local label mechanism
        Jerry Boutelle and I just built into F-PC. The new file NEWLAB.SEQ
        in F-PC allows a type byte to be applied to each unresolved
        forward reference. The assembler function RESOLVE_REF is later
        called when the forward reference is to be resolved. When a new
        assembelr is added, for a new target, the assembler will need to
        add a new resolve word if resolution types other than the standard
        four: RELATIVE-8, RELATIVE-16, (absolute) OFFSET-8 OR OFFSET-16
        are needed.

        Overall this results in a much cleaner way of resolving forward
        references.

 05/20/91               ***** TCOM Version 1.37 *****
                        ***** 8086 Version 2.08 *****

        Ran into another problem, which I hope is now solved. It seems
        there are a number of operations needed from F-PC at compile time
        in TCOM to perform their normal operation.  TCOM was thus
        searching the FORTH vocabulary after searching the TARGET, the
        COMPILER, and the ASSEMBLER.  It turns out there is a problem
        with this. If you are forward referencing a word that is defined
        in F-PC, then that word may under some conditions get executed
        (while assembling or interpreting) when you dont' want it to. The
        classic example of this is an application call to the target
        symbol COLD in the target. Since FORTH's COLD was accessible, the
        interpreter just executed COLD to get its address.  Naturally
        F-PC did a COLD restart which wasn't exactly what was desired.
        after discussions with Jerry, we think the only way to get around
        this type of problem is to prevent the compiler from EVER
        searching Forth for any words.  The way to do this in TCOM is to
        create another vocabulary called HOST and make aliased headers in
        this vocabulary for all of the Forth words needed by the target.
        Then setup the vocabulary search order so HOST is searched, but
        FORTH is not.  We have done this.

 05/24/91

        I (think I) have finally worked through the problems I introduced
        by switching to this new HOST vocabulary concept. You can now use
        the /FORTH, /DIS, and /DEBUG options and they work properly.
        Actually the problems I had with these words was primarily do to
        the change I made a while back in the memory format of the symbol
        tables when they were used.  In any case they now work.

        While debugging these problems, I noticed a peculiarity about the
        BIOS in the SAMSUNG computer I am using. If you accidently or
        otherwise position the computer cursor off the screen, then
        return to DOS, then it looks like the computer has locked up. In
        reality the screen simply is not scrolling, and the cursor is
        below the screen, so nothing you type shows up. As unobvious as
        it seems, the solution is to position the cursor to line 23
        before exiting a program to assure the cursor is really on the
        screen.  The computer I have at home doesn't have this problem.

 06/12/91               ***** TCOM Version 2.00 *****

        Add error file generation code. TCOM now makes a file called
        <filename>.ERR that contains any error messages associated with
        your compile. (later this was changed to <fileame> MSG)

 06/17/91

        Added TFILEIO.SEQ (for TCOM) and FILEIO.SEQ (for F-PC) to
        TCOMUTIL.ZIP. This file provides multiple file (line & block)
        buffered read and write to TCOM applications. A new set of words
        is provided with a "B" prefix to provide the needed operations.
        See TFILEIO.SEQ for further details.

 06/18/91

        Jerry found a bug in the buffered lineread at the end of the file.
        Fixed.

 06/20/91           ***** 8086 Library Version 2.11 *****

        Added long branch words to the 8086 library. They allow the
        correction of branch out of range errors by explicit "_L" long
        specification rather than having to use "long_branch" before and
        "short_branch" after any word that gives a branch out of range
        error.  The words are:

            IF_L    ELSE_L    WHILE_L   ?DO_L   LOOP_L   +LOOP_L

        The words UNTIL, REPEAT and AGAIN have been modified so they
        ALWAYS use a WORD branch distance.

        Removed all usages of LONG_LABEL from the samples that were using
        it, and changed to the _L words.

        Made a minor modification to the INDEX program, it is now
        actually possible to abort its operation by pressing ESC. It
        always said you could abort it, but it would ignore your key
        press, now it works.

        NOTE: THE ABOVE CHANGE WAS LATER BE NEGATED IN FAVOR OF THE
        WORD "[LONG]" INSTEAD.

 06/28/91         ***** 8086 Library version 2.12 *****
                       ***** TCOM version 2.01 *****

        Corrected a bug in S>D found by Jerry Boutelle. I was pushing the
        double number result in the wrong order.

        Made S,-T defered. Now almost all of the "-T" words are defered.
        These include:  ,-T  C,-T  !-T  C!-T  ALLOT-T  S,-T

 07/09/91

        Added Expanded memory support to TCOM in the form of a loadable
        file called TEMM.SEQ. An example of its use is included in the
        samples as the file EMMTEST.SEQ.

 07/19/91

        Reworked TCOM's line parsing routine. Added "/PRJ <filename>"
        parameter to the command line options. This option will
        EVENTUALLY allow TCOM to perform a build of a project, only
        compiling those file that have been changed. For now it just
        opens the filename following as the file to compile.

        NOTE: LATER THIS WAS DISCARDED.

 07/23/91              ***** TCOM Version 2.02 *****

        Split COMPILER.SEQ into two files appropriately named
        COMPILE1.SEQ and COMPILE2.SEQ.  The COMPILER.SEQ file was simply
        getting TOO BIG. It has been split more or less in the middle, to
        make it more managable.

        I continue to work on the project handling for TCOM, but its
        completion remains some distance in the future.

 07/24/91

        I have given up on the project concept, it turns out that
        unwinding the compiler to continue a compile from a particular
        point in an already performed compile is just too difficult
        (requires too many changes to TCOM).  I have switched over to
        another concept. The real goal in projects was to minimize
        compile time turn around when making small changes during a
        program debugging cycle. This can be accomplished by providing a
        two stage compile, where a stable portion of a program is
        compiled first, and then included (without recompiling) into a
        second compile.  This is accomplished by reading in the symbols
        and .COM file from the first compile, and then continuing to
        compile the second file.  This turns out to be much simpler than
        unwinding a previous compile since the only thing that carries
        over to the second compile is its symbols which can easily be
        re-read (quickly) into memory. This second scheme has been
        implemented, and seems to work. The whole process is still
        changing, so if you want to use this feature, you will need to
        include the file TCOMNDX.SEQ (uncomment it out) in TARGET.SEQ
        and re MAKETCOM.  You then include the first compiled file as
        follows:

                C:\> TCOM <second_file> /SYMFILE <first_file>

        or by including the following line in the second file near the
        beginning (before any code is compiled):

                        .SYMBOL-INCLUDE <first_file>

        Either of these will cause the symbols and .COM file from the
        first file to be read into memory and included into the second
        files compile.

        NOTE: LATER THIS WAS DISCARDED, AS IT WAS ONLY A PARTIAL
        SOLUTION.

 08/01/91               ***** TCOM version 2.05 *****
                    ***** 8086 Target Version 2.15 *****

        Many minor and major changes to TCOM. Adjusted VARIABLE,
        2VARIABLE and ARRAY so that when they are used in a target
        application, they define a name and allocate their needed data
        space immediately, without waiting for name to be used.  It is
        conceptually more space efficient to only allocate their space
        it they are used, but it turns out to be just too common for a
        user to do something like the following:

                VARIABLE XYZ 8 ALLOT

        In the old case, the variable XYZ wasn't allocated unless it was
        used at a later time, but the ALLOT worked instantly, and as
        such was not associated with the variable.  Changing variables so
        they allocate when defined, assurs much better code
        compatibility.

        :: change.  You used to have to use :: when defining a defining
        word, so the compiler could know what you were doing, and use the
        right function to compile your defining word.  TCOM now detects
        when you use the word CREATE in a ":" definition, unwinds any
        code already compiled, and switches to building a defining word.

 08/08/91               ***** TCOM version 2.06 *****
                    ***** 8086 Target Version 2.16 *****

        Modified TCOM so it doesn't terminate a compile unless a serious
        error occurs. And even if a serious error does occur, the
        application image file will still be saved, so the listing
        program can create a listing that will include any detected
        errors.  The only conditions that will prevent TCOM from saving
        the image file and generating a requested listing, is are disk
        errors.  Serious errors that will cause TCOM to terminate without
        a program save are:

                1. Invalid command line options
                2. Out of Host memory
                3. Disk write errors

        Added PLACEL and +PLACEL to the library. Fixed a bug in the error
        message routines, they were not writing the correct filename when
        an unresolved symbol from a nested file was displayed.

        PLACEL and +PLACEL were also added to F-PC (and are now needed by
        TCOM), so F-PC changed versions as well.

        Added ORG segment overlap checking. If the code from two or more
        segments overlaps, TCOM will issue an error warning.

 08/21/91           ***** 8086 Target Version 2.17 *****

        Added Control Break handling to TCOM.  The default initialization
        calls SAVE_VECTORS and SETUP_BREAK to install the control break
        handler. An additional function RESTORE_VECTORS is installed into
        a new VALUE BYE-FUNC. The contents BYE-FUNC is executed when a
        BYE is performed is BYE-FUNC is NON-ZERO. This allows an exit
        function to be performed on program termination if needed.  A
        "0 0 BDOS" not a BYE is not performed if your MAIN entry word
        just finishes execution, so you SHOULD end your programs with a
        BYE to assure BYE-FUNC gets a chance to perform any needed
        cleanup on program termination.

        If you do your own initialization (using /NOINIT), then you will
        have to naturally include the above words in your own
        initialization if you want Control Break handling to work.  If
        you don't, then pressing Control Break can lockup the computer.

 08/22/91         ***** 8086 Target Version 2.18 *****

        Added additional optimizers for conditional branches preceeded by
        "0=", "immediate =", "variable @", or "value". These optimizers
        significantly reduce space and save time on branch operations for
        "IF", "WHILE" and "UNTIL".

        Also fixed a couple of bugs in the optimizer area assiciated with
        index record deletion. Too many index records were being deleted
        when an optimize was performed by STORE_OPT2 and STORE_OPT3.

 08/27/91        ***** 8086 Target Version 2.19 *****

        Added TAIL OPTIMIZATION. When the following condition occurs;

                .... 2DUP ;

        which generates something like;

                ...
                CALL 2DUP
                RET

        Then TCOM changes it to;

                ...
                JMP 2DUP

        This saves one byte per occurance, and some small amount of time
        for the CALL that isn't done.

        Also added additional optimization, where the CALL is a forward
        reference, then TCOM recognizes the JMP to the next byte;

                ...
                JMP 2DUP
        2DUP    ....

        and deletes the JMP 2DUP altogether.  This last optimization can
        only be done where the forward referenced word is used only once
        in the definition, since TCOM won't know where other references
        in the definition were placed.

        Also improved the code generated by defining words. For example the
        following code;

                : xx create , does> @ ;

                3 xx v1
                4 xx v2

        used to generate code for V1 like;

        V1      DEC SI
                DEC SI
                MOV 0 [SI], BX
                MOV BX, # 3
                JMP XX

        While this isn't bad, it turns out to be possible to save some
        bytes in each defined word by moving the data address into AX
        rather than BX, and then adding code to the DOES> portion of XX
        automatically to save BX and move AX into BX. So the added code
        to the DOES> portion of XX looks like;

        XX      DEC SI
                DEC SI
                MOV 0 [SI], BX
                MOV BX, AX
                ...

        The code for each defined word then becomes;

        V1      MOV BX, # 3
                JMP XX

        a savings of four (4) bytes in each defined word, with a cost of
        one additional "MOV BX, AX" in the body of the DOES> word.

        Of course you really don't have to worry about this stuff. Since
        TCOM has full control of the generated code for both the DEFINING
        and DEFINED words, it is all transparent to the application.

        Also added a series of comments about tail optimization to the
        OPTIMIZ.SEQ file in the \TCOM\SRC directory.

 09/05/91        ***** 8086 Target Version 2.20 *****

        Added a critical error handler to TCOM applications. Critical
        errors just return a fail flag to the calling function rather
        than displaying the DOS Abort/Retry etc. message.

        Cleaned up some restore interrupt vector problems in the bye
        function in TCOM.  It seems the control break vector wasn't
        always getting restored properly. FIXED.

        Added a further optimization to the 8086 target. Dot-quote
        strings were being compiled as two LITs, follwed by a TYPE.  This
        was using more space than needed, so I hanged the target to
        compile a single LIT followed by a call to $TYPE. This saves
        about seven bytes per dot-quote occurance.

        The listing program LS86.COM is now quite refined. Jerry
        Boutelle's work on it has resulted in a very good listing being
        generated.  Listing generation is enabled by the /LST command
        line parameter on the TCOm command line. When TCOM finishes a
        compile, it invokes LS86 to generate the listing.  You can also
        make a listing later using LS86 if the program was compiled with
        the /INDEX directive which maked TCOM generate the appropriate
        index and symbol files.

 09/13/91               ***** TCOM Version 2.07 *****

        I have updated the currently available targets, to include a listing
        generator program for each target.  Changes have also been made to
        allow each target to generate the proper index and symbol files for
        use by the listing program. The targets that have listing programs
        are:

        8086, 80196, 6805, SAM8(Samsung only), 56000(Samsung only)

        The 8080 target has also been updated, but since it generates
        indirect threaded code, is not suitable for the listing program.

        The listing program now sorts the symbols alphabetically by name
        before writing them to the listing file. Before, they were simply
        written in definition order, which was mostly random.

        TCOM has a few more switches than it used to. Added are:

        /libafter       resolve forward references at end of compile
        /liba           aliases for /LIBAFTER
        /lib+
        /+lib

        /libin          resolve forward references at the end of each
                        colon definition.
        /libinside      aliases for /LIBIN
        /libi

        /lstlib         tell listing program to include library code in
                        generated listing.

        /lstnolib       tell listing program to not include library code
                        in the generated listing.

        The listing programs like LS86 allow user specification of whether
        the library code should be disassembled as part of the generated
        listing.  The listing programs accept the following switches:

        /lib            include the library in the generated listing.
        /nolib          don't include the library in the generated listing.

        I have added a generic target to TCOM (TCOMGEN.ZIP). This target
        which doesn't actually generate any programs, compiles messages to
        the display as it compiles a program. This allows you can see the
        relationship between the optimizer/linkage file and the library file
        to the compiler.  My hope is that TCOMGEN will make it at least
        somewhat easier to uderstand TCOM's internal workings.

 09/17/91

        Updated TFORTH.SEQ, DIS.SEQ and TDEBUG.SEQ to be compatible with
        the new symbol file format used by the listing generators. So the
        /FORTH, /DIS and /DBG command line options now work properly
        again with the 8086 target.

        Also updated TFLOAT.SEQ to be compatible with the multitude of
        changes I have made in the last six months.

 09/18/91

        Did cleanup today in listing program. Checked and corrected
        several bugs related to both compiling and making listings of
        very large programs. Modified TCOM to compile code and data into
        seperate buffers. This allows programs larger than 64k to be
        compiled although the 8086 still can only handle a 64k .COM file.
        TCOM will now save a .COM file larger than 64k, but it won't run
        under DOS. A warning is issued for compiles bigger than 64k.

        Made several changes to the listing program. Now displays
        approximate minutes and seconds remaining for listing generation.
        Also fixed some sign problems that cropped up when the index got
        bigger than 32000 records. I have successfully created listing
        files upto about 1.5 megabytes. The corresponds to about a 64k
        program.

        Due to the changes placing data in a seperate buffer, TCOM will
        be much less sensitive to the ratio of code to STATIC data.
        However the SUM of the two MUST still fit in 64k or the resulting
        program WON'T RUN!

 09/20/91       ***** 8086 Target Version 2.21 *****

        Added SETDIR and SETDRIVE to the the THANDLES.SEQ library. They
        provide the ability to set the current drive and directory.

 09/24/91               ***** TCOM Version 2.08 *****

        Added extensive segment overlap checking. The test is performed
        on compile completion. Both CODE and DATA segments are verified
        for an overlap condition.

 09/27/91

        Cleaned up TSREAD. Changed the name LRHNDL to SEQHANDLE to be
        more compatible with F-PC. Added the words $HOPEN, "HOPEN, $FILE,
        MAXNEST, HNDLS, SEQUP, SEQDOWN, CLOSE & ?FILEOPEN mostely for
        better compatibility with F-PC. These words now automatically do
        a LINEREAD_INIT if needed so the user won't have to doit. In F-PC
        HNDLS is an array of several handles, in TCOM it is a single
        handle. As such SEQUP will issue an error message if you try to
        switch up to the next handle. So SEQUP is there for
        compatibility, but you really can't use it.

        Changed all the sample applications to use SEQHANDLE instead of
        the old name LRHNDL.

        These changes make it easier to open a file in a TCOM program
        and read lines out of it. The word $FILE takes a string, moves it
        into SEQHANDLE, opens the file, and initializes LINEREAD to you
        are immediately ready to read lines out of the file. This is much
        easier than before.

        Displaying the lines of a file are now as simple as the
        following;

        : main  ( | <name> -- )
                DOSIO_INIT              \ init EMIT, TYPE & SPACES
                DOS_TO_TIB              \ move command tail to TIB
                bl word $file
                begin   lineread c@
                while   cr outbuf count 2- 0max type
                repeat  close ;

        The first two lines of the above definition are only required if
        you use the "/NOINIT" command line option. They initialize I/O
        and make the DOS command line available to WORD.

        Added stack depth change checking to TCOM. A warning will be
        issued if the stack depth changes across the compile of a line.
        Various things can cause this to happen, TCOM used to only issue
        an error message at the end of the compile if data was left on
        the stack. It still does, but now also issues a warning at the
        line where the error is likely to have occured. We issue only a
        warning, because there are valid reasons to leave data on the
        stack while interpreting, from line to line.

        Three new compiler options are associated with the above change.

                /STACK          Perform stack depth checking on every
                                line.
                /NOSTACK        Don't perform stack depth checking on
                                each line. (default)
                /NOSTACK1       Turn off stack depth checking for the
                                current line. Used in a source file where
                                you don't want to be warned about leaving
                                an extra item on the data stack.

        Added a file OPTIONS.DOC that lists the command line options for
        TCOM, they are again listed here for redundancy;

/CODE-START xxx Set the CODE starting address to address xxx.
/DATA-START xxx Set the DATA starting address to address xxx.
/DBG            Include the debugger in the target program (8086ONLY).
/DEBUG          Include the debugger in the target program (8086ONLY). alias
/DEFINIT        Include the default initialization code. (default)
/DEFINITOFF     Don't include the default initialization code.
/DIS            Include the disassembler in the target program.
/FORTH          Include a Forth interpreter in the target program.
/HEADER         Include symbol headers in the target program. (some targets)
/HELP           Display the first Help screen.
/HELP2          Display the second Help screen.
/IND            Generate an index file for the target program.
/INDEX          Generate an index file for the target program. alias
/INX            Generate an index file for the target program. alias
/INDEXOFF       Don't generate an index file for the target program. (default)
/+LIB           Resolve library function inclusions at end of compile.
/LIB+           Resolve library function inclusions at end of compile. alias
/LIBA           Resolve library function inclusions at end of compile. alias
/LIBAFTER       Resolve library function inclusions at end of compile. alias
/LIBI           Resolve library functions as they are referenced.
/LIBIN          Resolve library functions as they are referenced. alias
/LIBINSIDE      Resolve library functions as they are referenced. alias
/LIST           Generate a listing file.
/LISTING        Generate a listing file. alias
/LST            Generate a listing file. alias
/LSTLIB         Include library disassembly in listing.
/LSTNOLIB       Don't include library disassembly in listing.
/NODEBUG        Don't include the debugger code in the target program.
/NODIS          Don't include the disassembler code in the target program.
/NOHEAD         Don't generate symbol headers for functions. (some targets).
/NOINDEX        Don't generate an index file for the target program. (default)
/NOINX          Don't generate an index file for the target program. (default)
/NOLISTING      Don't generate an index file for the target program. (default)
/NOINIT         Don't include the default initialization code in the target.
/NOOPT          Don't enable the code optimizer. (default)
/NOREDEF        Don't allow functions to be redefined. (default)
/NOSHOW         Don't show the names of functions as they are referenced. (def)
/NOSRC          Don't show the source lines during the compile. (default)
/NOSTACK        Don't check the stack for a depth change on each line. (def)
/NOSYM          Don't generate a symbol file during the compile. (default)
/OPT            Enable code optimization for this compile.
/OPTOFF         Disable code optimization for this compile. (default)
/Q              Quiet compile, compiler output can be redirected with ">".
/QUIET          Quiet compile, compiler output can be redirected with ">".
/REDEFOK        Allow the redeinition of functions during the compile.
/SHOW           Display the names of functions are they are defined.
/SHOWOFF        Don't display the names of functions as they are defined. (def)
/SRC            Show source file lines are they are compiled.
/SRCOFF         Don't show source file lines as they are compiled. (def)
/STACK          Check each compiled line for a stack depth change.
/STAY           Stay in the compiler after finishing a compile. leave with /BYE
/SYM            Generate a symbol file during this compile.
/SYMBOLS        Generate a symbol file during this compile. alias
/SYMOFF         Don't generate a symbol file during this compile.


 10/02/91       ***** 8086 Target Version 2.22 *****

        Added -TRAILING, and SP>COL to LIBRARY.SEQ. Modified all of the
        sample programs to remove the definitions of -TRILING and SP>COL
        and use the library version.

        Added a new command line option, /0INIT. It disables ALL
        INITIALIZATION code for everything including stacks. The only
        thing that gets initialized is CS & DS. This commandline option
        should be used ONLY WITH EXTREME CAUTION. You will need to do all
        of your own initialization where needed. The primary use of thie
        option, is to generate very small code words.

 10/03/91

        Added code to the compiler to read the first 32 lines of the
        program being compiled, and look for .OPT, .OPTION or .OPTIONS
        and interpret the line following as compile options fo the
        current compile.  This allows each program to have its own
        default set of compile options that the programmer can set, but
        doesn't have to remember everytime he or she performs a compile.
        .OPTION can be place either inside or outside of a comment. It
        doesn't have to be in column 1, and only the first .OPTION in a
        file is used.

        TCOM actually looks three places for compile options now. First
        it looks at the "TCOM=" environment variable, then it looks for a
        .OPTION statment in the file being compiled, then it looks for
        options on the command line. This technique alloes defaults to be
        in the environment, defaults for a program to be in the program,
        and allows you to override the defaults on the command line if
        desired.

        Added "SCANW" to LIBRARY.SEQ. SCANW scans forward a word,
        searching a word at a time.

 10/10/91

        I have added a real source level debugger to the TCOM system. It
        is called "BUG", and naturally the source is included. It is now
        much easier to debug TCOM 8086 applications than ever before. The
        debugger even has a simple browser built into it.

        The most significant limitation it currently has, is that the
        INDEX array which links the .COM file to the source, is limited
        to 64k, which means that you can only debug programs with source
        upto about 32k (.com file).

 10/30/91               ***** TCOM Version 2.09 *****

        With the addition of the new debugger, it became apparent that
        VALUEs needed to be included in the target at the time they were
        defined, so their sumbols in the symbol table would reflect the
        actual source location of the value rather than the source
        location where the value was first referenced. A change to the
        compiler has been made to reflect this requirement.

 11/15/91

        Added "!CSP" to "(LM:)", it was not marking the stack level at the
        start of a MACRO definition.

 11/18/91

        I thought I had set the compiler default options to generate a
        symbol table. .FIL file and index file, but as it turns out, my
        environment defaults were making that the default, so I have
        changes the compiler to make these the default so you can use the
        BUG debugger without having to use a special command line option
        to be able to debug your programs.

 11/19/91               ***** TCOM Version 2.10 *****

        Implemented ' (tick) as a target word that returns the function
        address of the word following. Modified "IS" and "!>" so they can
        be used during interpretation to store a number off the stack
        into the data space of the word following. These MUST be followed
        by a DATA SYMBOL, not a Function.  So it is now possible to
        initialize defered words at application compile time, eliminating
        the old restriction that they had to be initialized at runtime.
        Do it as follows:

                : %XYZ          ( -- )
                                ." Hello 'xyz' ;

                DEFER XYZ       ' %XYZ is XYZ       \ init defered word

        You can also use ' (tick) and , (comma) during the compiling of a
        structure as follows:

                : FUNC1 ;       : FUNC2 ;       : FUNC3 ;

                CREATE DUMBO
                        0 , ' FUNC1 ,
                        1 , ' FUNC2 ,
                        2 , ' FUNC3 ,

        These changes were requested by Jerry Boutelle, and do make a lot
        of sense.

        ADDED JOIN to the LIBRARY.SEQ. It existed in F-PC, but was not in
        TCOM. It has been added.

 11/20/91

        Added "[", "]" and "LITERAL" to the compiler. You can now use
        them while in the middle of a :(colon) definition, to perform a
        compile time calculation, and have a literal compiled into the
        program. Example:

                create myarray 22 allot

                : aword         ( -- )
                                myarray 20 +               \ the old way
                                ... some code ...
                                [ myarray 20 + ] literal   \ a new way!
                                ... Some more code ... ;

        Here, the address of the end of the array is compiled rather than
        compiling the start of the array, and at runtime calculating the
        end of the array.

 11/27/91

        Corrected a bug in the optimizer, that was causing the last
        function in an EXEC: list to be compiled inline, rather than
        compiling a CALL to it. The TAIL optimizer does this for
        functions that are only called once in a definition, and are also
        called last in the definition. Modified EXEC: to turn tail
        optimization off for the current definition to prevent this form
        of optimization from occuring.

 12/05/91               ***** TCOM Version 2.11 *****
                    ***** 8086 Target Version 2.23 *****

        Added the CHIP directive to the compiler.  This is normally
        followed by a filename, which contains EQUATES for the I/O
        registers of the particular controller being used for this
        application.  The filename is loaded as a Forth file, with a
        default base of HEX being selected.  The base is restored upon
        return from the load. The primary difference between the CHIP
        directive and an INCLUDE is the default HEX base, and in addition
        the CHIP file source lines are not included in any generated
        listing file.

        Also included in the file TGRAPH a large number of additional
        graphics video mode selection words for various cards from
        different manufacturers.

        Cleaned up the /HELP command in TCOM. Reduced the /HELP to one
        screen by deleting all the default options. You can still find
        out what the options are by lookin at the file OPTION.DOC.

 12/11/91

        Added U,.R and UD,.R to the library.  These words display numbers
        right justified, with included commas at three digit intervals
        from the right. Example: "1234567. 1 UD,.R" displays as 1,234,567

 12/30/91

        Added a library file TSOUND.SEQ, to provide TONE support like
        F-PC. Also added TETRA.SEQ, the tetris game written by Marc
        Hawley.

 01/03/92               ***** TCOM Version 2.12 *****

        Tried a simple thing today, created a macro to use inside another
        code word, and expected it to simply expand into a series of
        instructions in the code word. WELL it didn't work. Seems a macro
        just returns its address when used in interpret state.  This has
        now been changed, macros always expand into their instructions
        when used in interpret state, unless they are followed by a
        EXECUTES> statment, then they do the word following the
        EXECUTES> instead of expanding their insturctions.  It is
        important for CODE words to return their address during
        interpretation, so you can CALL a code word from another code
        word. But MACRO's can't be CALLed from a code word so they need
        to just expand their instructions.

        Example:

        MACRO PUSHA     ( -- )          \ a macro to save most registers
                        PUSH DI         PUSH SI
                        PUSH BP         PUSH BX
                        PUSH DX         PUSH CX
                        PUSH AX         END-MACRO

        MACRO POPA      ( -- )          \ a macro to restore most registers
                        POP AX          POP CX
                        POP DX          POP BX
                        POP BP          POP SI
                        POP DI          END-MACRO

        CODE MYTEST     ( -- )
                        PUSHA           \ save all registers
                        ...             \ my other instructions
                        POPA            \ recover all registers
                        RET     END-CODE

 01/06/92

        Fixed a problem in TFLOAT. It was reporting a bunch of warnings
        for stack depth increases. These shouldn't have been shown, so I
        modified TFLOAT to turn off stack depth checking during the load
        of FLOAT4TH and TFLOAT.

 01/08/92

        Modified TWFL.SEQ's "DIRALLOC". It no longer trys to display an
        error message if the allocate fails. You need to use the
        condition of DIRSEG being zero to detect the allocation failure.
        See LOOK.SEQ, ZTREE.SEQ or IND.SEQ for examples.

 01/10/92           ***** 8086 Target Version 2.24 *****

        Modified /0INIT to perform a bit more initialization. Zero
        initialization is pretty severe. I have changes the init to
        initialize SI to 512 bytes below SP, and to push a ZERO (0) to
        the hardware stack so if a program performs a return at the end
        it will return to address zero, which contains a terminate
        process instruction (INT $20). The init overhead is only 23
        bytes. It still falls into whatever CODE or :(colon) definition
        is first in the source file.

        Here is a list of the /0INIT initialization code:

        $0100   MOV AX, CS              \ get a copy of the CODE segment
                ADD AX, # $E4F6         \ patched later to adjust for
                                        \ where the data really is.
                MOV DS, AX              \ Set the data segment
                mov bx, sp              \ get current stack pointer
                sub bx, # $200          \ adjust up to location of data stack
                mov si, bx              \ set stack pointer
                mov sp0 bx              \ set data stack top pointer
                mov bp, # $00           \ init BP to $0000
                push bp                 \ push return to address $0000
                ....                    \ further user application code

 01/13/92

        Added an option /NOTAILOPT, with aliases /TAILOPTOFF and /TAIL-
        to disable return optimization. Tail optimization works fine, but
        can make debugging more difficult. So.., you might want to use it
        when debugging.

 01/15/92

        Added DB and DW to TCOM. They are followed by a number or symbol.
        If the symbol is undefined, then it will be resolved as it is
        defined later. Unfortunately no MATH can be used in  DB or DW if
        the line contains an undefined symbol.

 01/23/92 SAMPLES addition

        Added PROF.SEQ to TCOMSAMP.ZIP, and PROF.COM to TCOMUTIL.ZIP.
        These are the source, and executable for a profiling utility for
        TCOM. PROF allows performance results to be accumulated for large
        TCOM programs. A file PROF.TXT is generated on completion of
        execution that contains the addresses of buckets that contain
        counts of locations in the profiled application where significant
        time is spent. PROF attaches to the DOS system clock, and looks
        at where the profiled application is each time a clock tick
        occurs. While ticks only occur 18 times a second, large programs
        still accumulate useful results for performance analysis.

 01/25/92       Free distribution of F-PC and TCOM at SV-FIG

        Distributed 28 copies to all attending that asked. Had about 40
        people attending.

 01/26/92

        Added additional checking to BUG to keep the user from forgetting
        to step into a TT[']. BUG now detects a TT['], and automatically
        puts a breakpoint after the word being looked up if the user
        presses Enter to just step over the tt['].  This works much
        better than just letting the program run to termination.

 02/12/92 12:26

        Added BRANCH_MARK to TCOMNDX.SEQ, it compiles a special type of
        index record to tell a debugger when it is about to step into a
        branch type word. This is needed for TCOMS8, and TCOM56.

        Added additional testing to DO_SYMBOL, to verify a symbol is
        really a target type word before trying to resolve and not create
        a symbol. Seems we get a conflict at times when trying to define
        a word that is defined in the target like ' (tick).

 02/21/92 12:00

        Added a command line option /KEY. This option waits for the user
        to press a key after finishing a compile when an error occurs
        during the compile.

 02/26/92 12:44         ***** TCOM Version 2.13 *****

        Modified TINTERP to check for wheather we are in the middle of
        assembling an instruction before automatically defining a forward
        referenced label. If we are, doit, and if we aren't, then issue
        an error message for undefined symbol.

        Also added stack depth checking to CONSTANT, VALUE, 2CONSTANT,
        and FCONSTANT to get a cleaner error report in the case where not
        enough parameters have been put on the stack for them.

 03/23/92 17:04

        Added TEXTFORM.SEQ to TCOMSAMP.ZIP. This is a relatively simple
        text formatter. It does a few interesting thing, like box
        paragraphs, draw horizontal lines, it builds an (unsorted
        currenlty) index of the document.  Probably not teribly original,
        but it was fun to write, and someone may learn something from it.

 03/26/92 12:23

        Modified the conditional branches in the TCOM 8086 library to
        perform match checking.

 03/30/92 11:00         ***** TCOM Version 2.14 *****

        Modified CODE and LABEL to detect redefinitions. They weren't
        performing the proper check. This could lead to problems
        particularly when interrupts were defined, installed into a
        table, and then defined again later.

 03/31/92 17:10

        Added library address range checking to COMPILE1.SEQ and
        COMPILE2.SEQ. I hope this doesn't cause problems down the road,
        but we will have to wait and see.

 04/03/92 15:10         **** Target Version 2.26 ****

        Added a new word "DEL_B/I", that deletes bytes and instructions
        from the already compiled code.  This saves a significant amount
        of repetition in the optimizer.

 04/15/92 13:46

        Added a new word [LONG] to be used before conditional branch words
        that need to use long branch instructions, rather than shorter
        relative branch instructions.

 04/21/92 12:17

        Modified the auto increment branch words to start at local label
        number 128, rather than starting at zero. Robert smith was using
        local labels in macros, and there were conflicts. Also moved the
        ?LEAVE local label from 20 to 127. Modified F-PC NEWLAB.SEQ to
        issue an error message if a local label that is already in use,
        is defined again.

 04/22/92 13:28

        Modified PASM.SEQ, to use "ERR, rather than ABORT", so TCOM can
        avoid the program abort in the case of an address out of range.  Now
        an error is still reported in the message and listing file, but the
        compile doesn't terminate.  This is useful so multiple error can be
        detected in a single compile pass.

 04/26/92 08:34         ***** TCOM Version 2.15 *****
                        **** Target Version 2.27 ****
        Modified TCOM to include a function "[Llong]" library long, to
        allow specifying a particular branch as long for a library
        function.

        A much more significant change is in the library, I have REMOVED
        ALL OF THE "_L" VERSION OF THE BRANCH WORDS. No more IF_L etc.  I
        am switching over to the "[long]" form of branch control in
        applications. The sample programs have been modified accordingly.
        This does lead to incompatibility with earlier programs, but also
        reduces the size of the compiler since the _L words are no longer
        present.

        I hope this doesn't cause you too much trouble. From an editing
        standpoint, you simply need to delete the trailing _L from
        whatever words were using it, and put a [long] at the just before
        the word that was using the _L.

        I think this is a much cleaner way to handle the long branch
        problem, and very clearly identifies those places where long
        branches are required.

 05/06/92 12:23

        Increased the .FIL limit to 32 files from the previous limit of
        16 files.  If your application has more than 32 files, the
        debugger will still work, but it won't be able to find the source
        for word in files above 32.

        Enhanced the debugger to use a GREEN background for the part of
        the stack that is beyond the top of the stack, and a RED
        background when the stack underflowed.  The stack items that are
        not above the top of the stack continue to be shown with a BLACK
        background.

 05/13/92 09:03

        Changed the /OPT so it doesn't enable tail optimization. You have
        to explicitly use /TAILOPTON to enable it.  Since it is less
        convenient to debug programs that have tail optimization enabled,
        I decided to opt for convenience over efficiency.  Once your
        program is debugged, you can always include the tail optimization
        directive in your .OPTIONS statment in the program.

 06/26/92 16:31

        Added .PATH statment, to allow the source file to set the search
        path to any files that are to be included in the source file.

 07/01/92 16:16

        Added code to RES_SYMBOL, to get it to resolve forward references
        in code words to colon definitions later in the application.
        TCOM was not reporting an unresolved symbol error when you used a
        forward reference from a code word to a colon definition, but it
        was also not resolving the reference.  FIXED

 07/09/92 14:07

        Added BIOSKEY from F-PC to the TCOM 8086 library.

 07/17/92 15:09

        Noticed and fixed a bug in TEND-CODE, it was using the END-CODE
        from F-PC, along with doing some things itself.  The problem was
        that F-PC's END-CODE was doing a REVEAL which was incorrectly
        unlinking words defined in the same hash chain, when a word was
        defined as a forward reference, and was then later resolved.

        TCOM creates code words as findable immediately, so END-CODE
        doesn't need to REVEAL them. FIXED

 07/24/92 15:54         ***** Version 2.17 *****

        Added two new symbol types, for {DS} = DATA SEGMENT, and {CS} =
        CODE SEGMENT.  This was done to allow for changes being made to
        SAMA (SAMSUNG ASSEMBLER) to add relocatability.  I hope to add
        relocatability to TCOM as well.

        Added two new fields to the symbol file record format, for
        SYMSEG# and SYMSCOPE.  These relate to changes to SAMA for
        relocatability.

        Removed the .INCLUDE-SYMBOLS and related directives from TCOM,
        again this is due to changes related to SAMA, and to future
        changes to support relocatability.

 07/27/92 08:16

        Renamed "INLINE" to "[MACRO:]".  There is a word in F-PC called
        "INLINE" that is used to allow entry of assembly language into a
        high level definition.  The function of "[MACRO:]" is to compile
        the function following it as a MACRO into the current definition.
        These two uses of the same word are NOT at ALL the same thing. I
        realize now, it was a mistake on my part to reuse the same word
        in two different ways.  This problem was reported by J”rg Staben
        in an indirect way, by his attempt to use the word INLINE to
        include some assembly language into a colon definition.  FIXED

 07/29/92 14:21

        Modified (NUMBER?), to dis-allow recognition of comma, dash and
        slash as double number conversion characters.  This will prevent
        undefined words like 3- and 3/ from erroneously appearing to be
        recognized by the compiler, when they are just converted to
        double numbers.

        Modified TINTERP to allow commas to be used to seperate the
        operands following the instruction in CODE words.  A word
        just scans the input line of CODE words, and changes commas to
        spaces. This is experimental, but seems to work.

 09/02/92 13:13 tjz     ***** Version 2.18 *****
        Modified MACRO-START to clear the local labels, so they can be
        used inside MACROS without getting already defined label
        problems.

 09/09/92 15:14 tjz
        Modified CMOVE, CMOVEL, PLACE, +PLACE, WORD and LINEREAD to user
        a MOVSW when possible, to improve the speed of transfer.

        Added ODD_ALIGN and EVEN_ALIGN to control alignment of the data
        space in the 80x86 target.  This is useful primarily because of
        the previous MOVSW modification, which is even faster if moving
        to an address that is word aligned.  Since most forth buffers are
        counted (they have a count byte at the beginning) it is better to
        ODD_ALIGN them, putting the count byte on an odd boundry, and
        making the data word aligned.

 09/15/92 16:51 tjz
        Added a new defered word LMACRO-START, which MUST be initialized
        in a similar fasion to MACRO-START.  The difference is that
        MACRO-START does a SETASSEM and an INIT_LABELS, and LMACRO-START
        only does a SETASSEM.  This is needed so that MACRO when used in
        a users target application can use local labels, yet will still
        function properly when I use it in the library where macros do
        need to use local labels, but DON'T need need to use them in a
        re-entrant way.

 09/18/92 11:16 tjz
        Changed the name of the install program from TCOMINST.COM to
        INSTALL.COM.  Renamed DI.COM to TCOMI.COM and DS.COM to
        TCOMS.COM.

 10/07/92 16:11 tjz     ***** Version 2.19 *****
        Found a bug in T:, it was sometimes (when a word being defined
        was already defined earlier) changing the previous definitions
        function. BAD NEWS!  Reworked the way defining words work, they
        used to rely on LAST to always contain the NFA of the work they
        are changing the operation of in DOES>, but that is unreliable in
        a system where forward references can cause words to be defined
        earlier, so now a new word CDOES> accepts the CFA of the word
        being changed on the stack.  It works great! FIXED

 10/14/92 17:42 tjz
        TCOM has received a Cross Reference Program called XREF.  It is
        written in Forth and compiled with TCOM, and it runs like blazes.
        It processes the listing file, into a new file with a .XRF
        extention.

 10/20/92 17:18 tjz
        TCOM now handles files that include tabs properly. It doesn't
        expand the tabs, it just converts them to spaces during
        compiling.  The SAMSUNG debuggers have been modified to handle
        this properly.

        Also modified the listing generator program LS1.SEQ to expand
        tabs when making the listing.

 10/28/92 11:52 tjz             "BUG" debugger enhancement
        Added a flag that will appear to the right of any symbolic branch
        or call, that displays a BLUE 'S' (for Source) when the branch or
        call goes to a location where the source is available, and
        displays a RED 'L' (for Library) when the branch or call is to a
        location where no source is available.  This is primarily useful
        to assist you in knowing when not to nest into a library routine
        which doesn't have source available.

        Also added a new command 'U' for go UP to the calling function.
        This is useful for those timew when you step into a routine and
        then decide you didn't want to nest.  'U' will execute to the
        address on the top of the return stack.

        WARNING!  If you use the 'U' command and there is no useful
        address on top of the return stack, then the program will just
        run to completion or crash, which ever comes first.

 10/28/92 14:55 tjz
        Added a words   ,LINE"-T   ,"-T   and  ,-T to the TCOM host
        vocabulary.  ,LINE"-T compiles a non-counted string into CODE
        space, and follows it with the CR & LF characters.  ,"-T
        compiles a counted string into CODE space, and  ,-T  compiles a
        word into CODE space.

 10/29/92 18:48 tjz
        Enchanced the BUG debugger, to include better data symbol display
        for Watch and also added a function symbol display to View.

 11/06/92 12:48 tjz
        Fixed a bug in LS1.SEQ that was effecting all listing generators.
        It was possible for the listing to get out of sync with the index
        file if a source line started in the first column.  FIXED

 11/16/92 12:36 tjz
        Added additional error checking to the compiler, to issue an
        error message if the user tries to redefine a word that is
        already defined in the library.

 11/19/92 11:16 tjz
        Added a simple MAKE program to TCOM.

 11/19/92 14:42 tjz
        Added 2@L (double fetch long) and 2!L (double store long) to the
        TCOM library.

        Fixed a bug in COMPILE2.SEQ, I had previously added additional
        error checking to detect an attemp to redefine a library word.
        It seems there was a minor bug that did detect the redefinition
        but didn't detect that it was in the library.  FIXED

 12/01/92 15:35 tjz
        Fixed a couple of bugs in the floating point support as reported
        by Mel Bramwood.  Seems I changed the way the compilers F# word
        was working, leaving things in an incorrect state.  Also added a
        file FLOATER.SEQ to TCOMSAMP.ZIP, to make it easier to figure out
        how to get started using the floating point words.

 12/08/92 14:41 tjz
        Modified BUG to allow longer command lines to be passed to a
        program being debugged.  Lines upto about 120 characters will
        pass through correctly.

 12/10/92 13:22 tjz
        Added MOUSE support to TCOM.  A new file TMOUSE.SEQ provides
        functions similar to F-PC.  An two additional example programs
        called DOODLE.SEQ and DRAW.SEQ. They illustrate the use of a
        mouse in graphics mode to draw on the screen in 320x200x16 and
        640x480x16 graphics modes.

        Also added a couple of additional example programs from Robert
        Smith, to assist in keeping track of your consulting time.  Be
        sure to see BEGTIME.SEQ and ENDTIME.SEQ in the \TCOM\SAMPLES
        directory.

 12/11/92 13:24 tjz
        Moved the files: THERC.SEQ, TGRAPH.SEQ and TMOUSE.SEQ into the
        \TCOM\SRC directory, and installed them into the compiler as a
        default part of the pre-compiled TCOM.EXE library.

 12/11/92 18:13 tjz
        Modified NEWLAB.SEQ in F-PC to allow nesting local label sets
        upto eight levels deep.  New words LLSET+ and LLSET- move up and
        down the local label set words.  This is primarily useful in the
        condition where you want to use a macro inside a code word, or
        another macro, and you use local labels in the macro.  The
        nesting prevents local label conflicts from occuring between
        unrelated code or macro words.

 12/17/92 15:21 tjz
        Bob found a bug in "#=IF_OPT" the "Immediate equal IF" optimizer.
        It was compiling an unsigned byte when it should have been
        compiling a signed byte for certain operations.  FIXED

 01/05/93 18:00 tjz
        Found that the changes to NEWLAB above were causing problems in
        macros.  It seems that the conditional macros IF, ELSE, etc. were
        using LLSET+ and LLSET-, when they shouldn't have been.  Added
        LMACRO and END-LMACRO back in to TCOM, only difference is they
        don't use LLSET+ and LLSET-, so branches get resolved properly.

 01/06/93 07:47 tjz  ***** Compiler V2.20 ***** Target 8086 V2.27 *****
        Just completed an update verify of all the sample programs.
        Found a few that didn't compile for various reasons, and repaired
        some additional minor bugs in the compiler as a result.  I think
        (and hope) the local label problems have finally been solved.
        Added ZIM, a limited text file compression program to the samples
        as well.

 01/14/93 10:35 tjz
        Removed the ASSEMBLER vocabulary from the search order except
        when assembling code words.  It seems an attempt to define a
        colon definition with the name TEST was crashing the computer.
        The problem was that TEST is an instruction mnemonic, and was
        being detected as an existing target word when the new TEST was
        being defined.  This caused the compiler to try resolve a
        reference to TEST to the mnemonic instead of creating a new
        symbol for the new word TEST.

 01/19/93 10:04 tjz
        Added error checking to TCOM (COMPILE1.SEQ) to detect and notify
        the user of an error condition when they create a program that
        contains no colon definitions.  At least one definition is
        required if the program entry point is to be set properly.

 01/20/93 11:21 tjz
        Added BINEDIT.SEQ to TCOMSAMP.ZIP.  BINEDIT is an example program
        that allows binary editing of any file in either hex or ascii.

 01/20/93 12:45 tjz
        Found and fixed a bug in SEARCH that was preventing it from
        working on searches longer than 32k.

        Also finally figured out that the VIDEO-TYPE word in TVIDEO.SEQ
        was the culprit that was making the cursor disappear on exit from
        some TCOM programs.  It was trying to move the cursor to a
        location beyond the bottom of the screen, and this causes the
        cursor to disappear on some computers.  Corrected by clipping the
        position to which VIDEO-TYPE will position the cursor to ROWS-1.

 01/21/93 10:53 tjz
        Found that the &> (address of) operator was returning the address
        of the function in the case where it is being used on a CREATE
        DOES function.  It should have been returning the data field
        address.  CORRECTED

 01/21/93 13:18 tjz
        Added the VED virtual editor to the TCOMSAMP.ZIP file.  Also
        modified TESTALL.BAT to always use TESTALL.LST for its output
        file, and put in comments to tell the user what each program is
        as it is being compiled.

        Also added some additional optimization to all immediate
        operations, such as the folliwng:  +, -, and, or, xor, 1+, 2+,
        1-, 2-.


 01/22/93 14:05 tjz  ***** Compiler V2.21 ***** Target 8086 V2.28 *****
        Corrected a couple of problems with defining words.  The address
        being returned to the DOES> portion of a word was off by one, and
        when &> was used on a create does word it returned the address of
        the function rather than the functions data address. FIXED

 01/26/93 09:59 tjz
        Found a code imcompatibility between the current version of CMOVEL
        and the older version of CMOVEL that wasn't optimized to move
        words instead of bytes.  I have commented out the lines in CMOVEL
        that perform the optimization.

 02/02/93 16:00 tjz
        Found yet another bug in the SEARCH routine, if the string being
        searched was exactly 1 character long, then a wrap around
        condition would occur, making SEARCH look beyond its allowed
        search area.  FIXED

 02/08/93 14:22 tjz
        Jerry Modrow points out that the word CMODE! that is used in
        GRAPH.SEQ to select the video modes for F-PC should select SLOW
        to allow text to be drawn on the screen.  Added SLOW to CMODE!.

        He also points out that CPOINT, the word that returns the color
        of a point of the screen should mask off the high byte of the
        color, since it will often be returned as nonzero, indicating an
        invalid color.  Corrected in both GRAPH.SEQ and TGRAPH.SEQ

 02/12/93 12:48 tjz
        Jorg Staben reports problems with redefining words in an
        application even when the /REDEFOK directive is included in the
        .OPTIONS statment.  In looking at the code, there were some
        problems with redefining MACROs, since they didn't ever increment
        the usage counters.  This has been corrected, and a warning will
        now be given if a word is redefined that has already been used by
        the application.

 02/12/93 14:30 tjz
        Added functions MOUSE.SENSE@ and MOUSE.SENSE! to TMOUSE.SEQ.
        These are useful when MOUSE.LIMIT! is set to large values for
        higher resolution video modes.  You should save and restore the
        mouse sensitivity values.

        Also added MANGEN.SEQ and MANSHOW.SEQ, two programs that work in
        graphics mode and generate or show mandelbrot plots.

 02/16/93 12:35 tjz
        Added a new commandline parameter to ZTREE, it can now delete
        entire drives and or directories of files.  See ZTREE.SEQ for
        further information.

 02/17/93 14:06 tjz
        Added three new commands to TCOM's BUG debugger as follows:

        TAB     TAB key, prompt for a hex number and push it onto
                the application programs Data Stack.

        Del     Delete key, discard one item off the application
                programs Data Stack.

        ^Ins    Control-Insert key, moves the browse point and the
                Program Counter to the word nearest the screen
                cursor.  This is in effect a command to set the PC
                to here.

 03/03/93 10:50 tjz
        Added sorting to TWFL.SEQ. The word SORTDIR can be used after
        using $GETDIR, or is done automatically when you use GETDIR, to
        provide a sorted list of directory files.

        Added additional error reporting to DO and ?DO.  Nesting of DO or
        ?DO loops inside of a ?DO loop is not allowed, and will not
        resolve properly, so an error is now reported if you try to nest
        a DO or ?DO inside another ?DO conditional structure.

 03/08/93 15:59 tjz
        Added a new option "/CLEAN" to the compiler.  It discards any
        data files created by the compiler during the compile as
        specified by other options.  Specifically the applications .LST,
        .SYM, .INX, .FIL and .MSG files are not generated, or are deleted
        if generated by a seperate program (like the listing generators).

        This is primarily useful to override a set of default options
        contained within a source file, when final debugging is complete,
        and the additional data files will no longer be needed for
        debugging.

        If an error occurs during the compile, then at least a .MSG file
        will be generated anyway.

 03/10/93 15:25 tjz
        Modified MAKE.SEQ to allow adding a message to the string search
        and abourt function.

        Modified LS1.SEQ, to ignore the fact that a source file is not
        available, and just do a disassembly under those conditions.

 03/16/93 09:10 tjz
        Found a bug in the 8086 optimizer.  It was under some very
        special conditions trying to optimize code before the beginning
        of a function, into the code of the previously ended function.
        Added an OPT_OFF1 to the code in END-CODE, to prevent this.

 03/17/93 15:10 tjz
        Added RINGS.SEQ, a graphics sample to TCOMSAMP.SEQ.
        Added below zero clipping to CPLOT in TGRAPH, to prevent the
        incorrect screen wrap around I had observed when a program tried
        to plot a point above or to the left of the screen.

 04/02/93 14:47 tjz
        Found a bug in the DROP optimizer.  It was supposed to be
        incrementing the return stack pointers if it encountered
        "R> DROP", but was actually incrementing the data stack.  FIXED

 04/02/93 15:17 tjz
        Added a couple of new features to TCOM.  The '|' (vertical bar)
        symbol tells TCOM co place the header of the word about to be
        defined in the HTARGET vocabulary.  It will show up if used, but
        will not normally be find-able during a compile by the
        application.  Also added 'I|' (I vertical bar), to make a library
        symbol that is headerless. It works with any defining word.

 04/05/93 16:23 tjz     TCOM all targets
        Found a bug in ?DUP.  ?DUP is a macro , and should have been
        turning off the optimizer for a single operation, and was not.
        This problem showed up in that incorrect code was being generated
        under some conditions when ?dup was followed by an IF.  FIXED

 04/07/93 16:24 tjz     ***** TCOM 8086 target Version 2.29 *****
        Found that the optimizers for IF were not fully testing the
        preceeding code. Under the following conditions:
        " DUP 0= DUP IF "  the optimizer would try to double optimize the
        " DUP 0= DUP " completely out of existence.  Corrected by adding
        additional testing to detect the first optimizer already
        happening when the second optimizer tries to test for its valid
        condition.

        Added a new optimizer OVER_OPT, that tests for a preceeding over
        operation, and deletes it if present.  This is useful for things
        like " OVER - " or " OVER + ", which can better be done directly
        from the stack to BX instead of performing all the stack
        operations to perform the over first.

        Also added an optimizer for repeated literals.  Detects a repeat
        occurance of the same literal being pushed on the stack, and
        eliminates the extra " MOV BX, # xxxx ", since the literal is
        already in BX, and doesn't need to be reloaded.

 04/12/93 09:40 tjz
        Added COLOREMIT to the library.  It is automatically used by
        DOSIO_INIT instead of (EMIT) when no I/O redirection is detected.

        Also added two words which are used by DOSIO_INIT, that return a
        flag telling whether the DOS I/O redirection operators "<" and
        ">" were used on the DOS commandline.

          ?IN_REDIRECT    Returns f1=true if console input redirected
          ?OUT_REDIRECT   Returns f1=true if console output redirected

        DOSIO_INIT now detects I/O redirection, and select (EMIT)
        instead of COLOREMIT when I/O redirection is in effect.  This
        adds about 150 bytes to a program.

 04/13/93 16:28 tjz
        Added a command 'A' to the BUG debugger, to allow setting the
        arguments for the current program.  This is primarily useful when
        you want to specify I/O redirection, with the '<', or '>'
        symbols, which can't be used on the DOS commandline.

        Also added TSR.SEQ to TCOMSAMP.ZIP.  TSR is an example program
        that implements a relatively simple tarminate and stay resident
        program to perform number conversion.  It is invoked with the
        SCROLL LOCK key.  It also properly tests the "INDOS" flag, and
        does not pop up if DIS is busy.

 04/16/93 15:04 tjz
        Added two additional TSR examples called: TSRCLOCK and TSRIDLE.
        TSRCLOCK displays the current time in the upper right hand corner
        of the screen.  TSRIDLE waits for ten minutes to go by after the
        last keystroke and then invokes IDLE.BAT which can contain your
        favorite screen saver.

        Full TSR install and remove capability is provided, and you can
        even perform DOS file operations from within the TSR if you
        desire.

 04/30/93 15:53 tjz & rls
        Found some bugs that I put in when I coded D<SHIFT and D>SHIFT in
        assembly language.  Fixed the bugs in these.  Also found bugs
        related to FPARTS which was being used by E. and F., changed
        FPARTS into two words F.PARTS for F. and E.PARTS for E. since
        they really needed different functionality.

 05/14/93 17:17 tjz
        Added the TCOM program path to the FPATH, so extra utility files
        like those for floating point and graphics can be accessed from
        any directory without having to specify the directory.

        Robert and I also found some additional bugs in the FLOAT4TH and
        TFLOAT files.  FIXED.

 05/17/93 09:19 tjz
        Changed WORD to use EXECUTES> instead of NO-INTERPRET, so it can
        be used in defining words.  Added NUMBER so it can be used in
        defining words.  I guess defining words will always be somewhat
        limited in TCOM, but now you can do the following:

        : GMODE         ( -<mode hdots vdots segment size>- )
                        CREATE
                        bl word number drop ,   \ mode
                        bl word number drop ,   \ horizontal dots
                        bl word number drop ,   \ vertical dots
                        bl word number drop ,   \ video segment
                        bl word number drop ,   \ screen size in bytes
                        DOES>
                        length >r               \ save the mode number
                        length !> HDOTS         \ set horiz resolution
                        length !> VDOTS         \ set vertical res
                        length !> VID.SEG       \ set video segment
                        @      !> VID.SIZE      \ and screen size
                        r> vmode! ;             \ select the video mode

        Now we can define various graphic modes selection words.

        \     Graph mode        Mode Hor Ver Clrs Seg   Size
        GMODE 640x350x16        $10  640 350  16 $A000 $9600 \ EGA,VGA
        GMODE 320x200x256       $13  320 200 256 $A000 $FA00 \ VGA
        GMODE 800x600x16_OAK    $52  800 600  16 $A000 $FA00 \ OAK
        GMODE 800x600x16_TSENG  $29  800 600  16 $A000 $FA00 \ TSENG
        GMODE 640x350x256_TSENG $2D  640 350 256 $A000 $FA00 \ TSENG

        While the above is very nice, it won't work in a library, since
        defining words are not supported in a library currently.  So you
        WON'T find this method used in the file TGRAPH.SEQ.  It is still
        a nice capability for use in an application program.  By the way,
        the above technique also saves significant space in a target
        application by applying only a five byte of code overhead to each
        word defined, in addition to the data specific to the word.

 05/17/93 10:48 tjz
        At the suggestion of Mike Mayo, I have modified all of the
        backward branch words like UNTIL, LOOP and +LOOP to automatically
        test and compile a word backward branch if required, rather than
        just giving an error message.  The words REPEAT, NEXT and AGAIN
        already compiled word branches.  The word [LONG] must still be
        used when a long forward branch occurs with the words with IF,
        ELSE, WHILE or ?DO.  Making these automatically compile the right
        size forward branch is not impossible, but is much harder.

 05/18/93 17:59 tjz
        Mike Mayo has updated the TCOM graphics support, and I have
        integrated it into TCOM, replacing TGRAPH.SEQ with GRAPH.SEQ.
        GRAPH is generalized to work with either TCOM or F-PC.  Mike also
        updated HERC.SEQ, to be loaded after GRAPH.SEQ, and to be
        optional.  GRAPH-INIT has been eliminated, just use ?VMODE to
        test the current video mode.  All examples have been updated to
        reflect the new arraingment.  Words GTEXT-ON AND GTEXT-OFF are
        used to enable or disable the drawing of text characters in
        graphics modes.  Drawing characters allows them to be drawn on a
        pixel boundry, rather than on a character boundry.  You can also
        specify the background color as well as the forground color for
        the characters.  They are drawn somewhat slower than the BIOS
        draws them however, and they are drawn using the 8x8 character
        cell rather than the default 9x16 cell that the BIOS uses.

 05/19/93 15:41 tjz     ***** TCOM 8086 target Version 2.30 *****
        Added a direct graphics screen point plot routine for graphics
        modes 640x350x16 and 640x480x16.

        Added support for properly selecting the bit planes when drawing
        after turning on or off the mouse cursor.

 05/20/93 12:56 tjz
        Modified the file TSHAPES.SEQ to be compatible with F-PC as well
        as TCOM, and have thus renamed it to SHAPES.SEQ.  Removed
        THERCTXT.SEQ, its functionality is no integrated into the files
        GRAPH.SEQ and HERC.SEQ.

 05/21/93 15:26 tjz
        Added 8X14FONT and 8X8FONT to select between two of the available
        EGA/VGA fonts.  8X14FONT is selected automatically when
        640x350x16 or 640x480x16 graphics mode is selected.  Otherwise
        the BIOS font is selected.  8X8FONT can be selected if you have
        an EGA or VGA and want to use the characters above 127.

        Don't try to use these words if you have a hercules, they won't
        work.

        NOTE: While hercules has been adapted to the new format of
              GRAPH.SEQ, it has not tested, so it may well NOT WORK!

 05/27/93 13:41 tjz     ***** TCOM Compiler Version 2.22 *****
        Added an alias /C to /CLEAN.

 06/01/93 13:57 tjz     ***** TCOM Compiler Version 2.23 *****
        Removed commandline options /FORTH, /DIS and /DBG. They are not
        needed now that TCOM includes the BUG source level debugger.

        Added a compiler performance line, that indicates compile time in
        seconds, lines compiled and byte compiled per second.

 06/02/93 11:12 tjz
        Added optimizers to MIN, MAX, UMIN and UMAX to detect a previous
        literal or absolute.  These optimizers make the above words
        compile as macros instead of CALL's, saving execution time, and
        still save one or two bytes of code space per occurance.  If no
        optimization is possible, then they are referenced with a CALL,
        and the code generated is identical to previous versions of TCOM.

 06/10/93 14:03 tjz
        Enhanced ZTREE.SEQ to allow unpaused multi directory delete
        operations.  ZTREE used to pause and prompt Y/N if you used a
        delete of "*.*".  This is no longer the case, It now feeds DOS a
        'Y' character to force DOS's DEL command to accept the delete.

 06/15/93 14:39 tjz
        Added several new items to TCOM.  A TCOM compile option /COMPRESS
        or /LZ will now produce a .COM file output that is compressed
        using the new LZ file compression utility.  Programs compressed
        in this way are still executable, but are about 45% smaller than
        normal TCOM programs.

        Added programs LZX.SEQ and LZ.SEQ to the TCOM sample files.
        LZX.SEQ is a primitive utility that is used in binary form by
        LZ.SEQ when building compressed .COM files.  LZ.SEQ is a file
        compression and decompression tool that will compress or
        decompress data or program (.COM) files.  LZ.COM is invoked by
        TCOM when the /COMPRESS or /LZ switch is used.  Note that
        compression is fairly slow, and should only be used after a
        program is fully debugged.  ALSO NOTE THAT THE DEBUGGER CAN'T
        DEAL WITH COMPRESSED FILES.

        Added BINLOAD-DATA and BINLOAD-CODE to TCOM, so it would be
        possible to create LZ.COM which needed to load LZX.COM as part of
        its data.

 06/23/93 15:01 tjz
        Recovered the profiler PROFILE.SEQ and added it to the samples
        .ZIP file.  Currently PROFILE.SEQ must be included at the start
        of any application you want to profile, and then you must insert
        PROSTART and PROEND around the area of the origram you want to
        profile.  Evantually I hope to make the profiller a seperate
        program.

 07/13/93 13:00 tjz
        Updated LZ.SEQ to allow "-" options in addition to "/" options,
        and to allow using a filespec like *.SEQ with the /A option.
        Also modified the /X option to extract all files is no filename
        is specified after the file.LZ.  Updated the online help.

 08/17/93 10:58 tjz
        Fixed a bug in XREF, it would crash if it ran out of memory.

 01/24/94 14:47
        Added OPT_OFF1 to DO_SYMBOL in COMPILE1.SEQ.  Under some
        conditions, the optimizer wouldn't function properly because it
        would improperly detect an optimizable condition before the current
        colon definition being defined.  DO_SYMBOL should have been
        disabling optimization under some conditions.

 01/26/94 11:36
        Modified COMPILE1.SEQ so it only paragraph aligns CODE space
        saved when there is more than two bytes of DATA space included in
        the target application.  Since DP is always included (2 byte) in
        the target application, then data space will only be needed if DP
        is greater than two.  This allows extreamly tiny applications to
        be built, containing only code, and no data.  The example at the
        end of FORM.SEQ is an example of a 9 byte program that sends a
        formfeed to the printer.

 01/26/94 12:47
        Added ;- (semicolon minus) to OPTIMIZ.SEQ. It can be used when no
        RET is needed at the end of a COLON definition.

 01/27/94 14:03
        Fixed a bug in the &> operator that was preventing it from
        working inside a macro assembly language word.  This was done by
        making "res_comp_&value" smart enough to know that a macro was
        being created.

 01/27/94 14:21
        Modified %T['] to detect the case where the function being looked
        up is already defined, and it then just compiles a literal for it
        rather than using TT['] which is a large routine.  Result is the
        six bytes, the same as if TT['] was used, but TT['] is not
        included in the application, which saves about 20 bytes.

 02/01/94 16:16
        Added optimizers to ELSE and ENDOF, to detect when they are
        preceeded by EXIT and optionally a CALL instruction.  If an EXIT
        preceeds them, then the jump to ENDIF or ENDCASE is not compiled.
        If a CALL also preceeds the RET, then the CALL is changed to a
        JMP and the RET is removed.  The optimization is enabled by the
        commandline options /TAILOPTON.

        Also added EXITOF, a word that is used in place of ENDOF, that
        compiles an EXIT and doesn't compile a branch to ENDCASE.  It
        also performs the same optimization that EXIT ENDOF performs.

        Also added $" (dollar sign quote) to the list of available target
        words.  It is like " (quote), but it compiles a counted string
        returning the address of the string rather than address and
        length of the string.   Again, this word can sometimes be used to
        save some bytes if you are so inclined.

 02/14/94 16:33
        Modified COLOREMIT to use a word register when testing #LINE.  It
        was wrapping around to the top of the display at 256 lines.  It
        will still wrap around to the screen top at 65536, but few
        programs will output that many lines to the screen.

 03/11/94 15:46
        Re-factored TVIDEO.SEQ slightly for better compatibility with
        F-PC. Split VMODE.SET in TVIDEO into two words, called
        VIDEOIO_INIT and FAST.  VIDEOIO_INIT is like DOSIO_INIT, but is
        for the direct to video functions.  The .._INIT words should only
        be used once, then FAST or SLOW can be used to switch between the
        two video methods if needed.

 03/11/94 15:51 tjz     ***** TCOM Compiler Version 2.40 *****
 03/11/94 15:51 tjz     ***** TCOM 8086 target Version 2.40 *****

 03/22/94 18:15
        Modified TRUN in COMPILE2.SEQ.  Added detection for a word at the
        beginning of a line, when undefined and ending with a colon ':'
        automatically as a new label. This enhances compatibility with
        assembly language. This automatic label creation is enabled by the
        /ASM_LABELS option while in a Forth program, or by /ASM when the
        program contains assembly language ONLY.  /ASM is an alias for
        /CUSTOM_INIT which disables all target initialization and begins
        execution at the first byte of program code encountered.

 03/23/94 10:46
        ****************** WARNING SIGNIFICANT CHANGE *******************
        Changed the DEFAULT compiler options to /CLEAN.  This means no
        debugger data files are generated any longer by default.  To make
        the compiler generate the data files needed for debugging a
        program, use the new /DEBUG option, which will turn on .SYM, .FIL
        and .INX file generation.  NOTE: The /LST option used to generate a
        listing file will also turn on /DEBUG, since the listing generator
        needs these files to generate the listing file.

        This change has little effect on the operation of the compiler, but
        will minimize the exteranious data files the user sees unless they
        are specifically trying to debug a program.  The overall result of
        this change, is simply that you will need to include the /DEBUG
        option in your .OPTIONS list in your program source file until you
        get your program debugged.

 03/23/94 10:53 tjz     ***** TCOM Compiler Version 2.50 *****

 03/24/94 10:17 tjz
        It is useful I think to note again the locations and order of
        places where compiler options can come from.  First there are
        five(5) places where compiler options can come from, they are
        (in LOAD order, which is the REVERSE of precedence):

                1.      Local directories TCOM.CFG.
                2.      If local TCOM.cfg is NOT present, then the
                        TCOM's execution directory file TCOM.CFG.
                3.      The TCOM directive in the environment if present.
                4.      The .OPTIONS directive in the source file.
                5.      The commandline.

        The higher numbered items above will take precedence over lower
        numbered items, so the "commandline" options will override any
        options previously encountered.

        Item three(3), the environment, though still available should
        generally not be used, since there are often space problems with
        environment variables.  They don't provide any advantage over using
        TCOM.CFG for the compiler defaults anyway.

        With the change of 3/23/94, to the /CLEAN options as the default,
        you may well find is useful to create a TCOM.CFG with the /DEBUG
        option in it to avoid having to put the /DEBUG options in your
        source files while debugging.

 03/24/94 10:42 tjz
        Added a warning.  When a compile has errors,if the /CLEAN options
        was used, then warn the user that a recompile with the /DEBUG
        option will be needed before debugging.

 03/30/94 17:34 tjz
        Minor modifications to support the /DRIVER option.  Enhancements
        to allow putting a label on a line ending in a colon (:),
        interspersed with other words without worrying about
        vocabularies.

 04/19/94 20:49 tjz
        Removed the environment variable support for "SET TCOM=".  I found a
        bug in the environment words, and since the environment variable for
        TCOM is not needed any more, due to the convenience of keeping
        compiler options in the source file, I remove the environment
        variable.  If it is needed by someone, then it can be added back in
        by editing COMPILE1.SEQ (look for "TCOM=").

 08/15/94 15:22 tjz
        It was reported that the TCOM optimizer for the 8086 was
        incorrectly TAIL optimizing the sequence when ['] was used before
        a function at the end of a colon definition:

                ..... ['] function ;

        When this was done, the definition just fell into the following
        definition and never returned.  This is not good, and has been
        corrected.



